<HEADLINE> Iraq Nearly Completes Oil Contracts Under UN Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Oil Minister Amr Mohammed
Rashid said Friday that Iraq has concluded oil contracts worth 95
percent of the total sums allocated for food and medicine under
the third phase of the Iraqi-U.N. oil-for-food deal.
</P>
<P>
Rashid told a news conference that Iraq has concluded 29
contracts with world oil companies, 23 of them have been approved
by the U.N. Sanctions Committee.
</P>
<P>
Under the third phase of the oil-for-food program, Iraq is
allowed to sell 2 billion U.S. dollars worth of oil to buy food,
medicine and other humanitarian supplies for its people in another
six-month time.
</P>
<P>
According to the Iraqi-U.N. Memorandum of Understanding signed
in 1996, 1.3 billion dollars out of the 2 billion dollars will be
earmarked for the purchase of food and medicines, some of the rest
will go to U.N. Special Commission in charge of eliminating Iraq's
weapons of mass destruction, and some will be used to compensate
the victims of the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
The oil minister said that the processes of loading Iraqi oil
to the world markets continue in accordance with the approved
contracts via the Iraqi Al-Bakr port and the Turkish Ceyhan port.
</P>
<P>
Rashid added that Iraq is ready to meet any future increases in
the capacity of the crude oil export in case of any increase in
the sum of the oil-for-food deal.
</P>
<P>
Iraq is suffering from a devastating economic embargo imposed
by the United Nations after its invasion of Kuwait seven years
ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
