<HEADLINE> UK Miners' Historic Win May Cost Govt Huge Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Six ex-miners won a legal battle
on Friday to prove their chest diseases were caused by coal dust
-- leaving the government with a 1 billion-pound (1.6 billion U.S.
dollar) bill.
</P>
<P>
Six out of eight retired miners who brought a test case in
London's High Court against their former employers, the
nationalized company British Coal, were awarded initial
compensation of between 2,400 and 9,000 pounds (4,000 and 11,000
dollars). Two failed because of lack of medical evidence.
</P>
<P>
The cases will set a precedent for another 162 claims already
lodged and thousands of others to be processed.
</P>
<P>
The judgement could lead to the largest damage payout ever seen
in the UK of well over 1 billion pounds altogether.
</P>
<P>
Legal action in the current cases began in 1990, but
compensation claims could date back to 1947 when the coal industry
was nationalized.
</P>
<P>
Lawyers believe thousands of miners were exposed to excessive
levels of coal dust, many developing chronic chest conditions such
as bronchitis and emphysema.
</P>
<P>
"This is legal history. It will lead to the highest
compensation bill ever for a single British employer running into
hundreds of millions of pounds (dollars)," Tom Jones, a lawyer who
represented one of the men, said.
</P>
<P>
British Coal, once the largest employer in Europe with a
million miners, ceased to exist when Britain's then Conservative
government privatized the coal industry in 1994. Any compensation
bill would be picked up by the government's Department of Trade
and Industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
