<HEADLINE> Cyprus, Russia to Expand Economic Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus and Russia have agreed
to expand economic and trade cooperation through a series of
measures and agreements signed in Moscow, Cyprus News Agency
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
During the first session of the joint intergovernmental
committee on trade and economic cooperation between the two
countries, which was held in Moscow Thursday, two agreements, on
agriculture and the prevention of calamities, were signed by
Cyprus Finance Minister Christofoulos Christodoulou and Russia's
First Deputy Finance Minister Alexei Kudrin.
</P>
<P>
Regarding investment, the two sides decided to set up a joint
task-force which will monitor the implementation of the measures
agreed.
</P>
<P>
They also decided to set up a special joint committee made up
of businesspeople to plan and coordinate relations regarding
investments.
</P>
<P>
Cypriot Finance Minister Christodoulou said during the meeting
the Cypriot government's intention to spend 1 million U.S.
dollars as financial support to Cypriot businesspeople seeking to
operate in Russia.
</P>
<P>
The Russian delegation announced a plan to set up a center in
Cyprus to promote Russia as an investment destination.
</P>
<P>
According to Russian Embassy in Cyprus, the bilateral trade in
1996 reached 553 million U.S. dollars, while about 1.5 billion
dollars is Cypriot investments in Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
