<HEADLINE> Canada's Retail Sales Down in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Canada's retail sales dropped
1.2 percent in November to 19.5 billion dollars (13.4 billion
USD), following a modest increase in October, Statistics Canada
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
"The decline was broadly based across almost all retail sectors
and all provinces," the statistics agency said.
</P>
<P>
A number of possible factors may be responsible for the drop.
Some retailers suggested that the winter weather played a role in
consumers putting off spending.
</P>
<P>
The increase in the interest rates, the weakening of the
Canadian dollar and turbulence in stock markets may have also
contributed to the drop.
</P>
<P>
Canada's retail sales have generally been rising since early
1996, strong advances were posted from the fall of 1996 to the
fall of 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
