<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Pakistan Tries to Achieve Food </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 23 (Xinhua) -- To get the nation out of a
persisting food crisis and achieve food self-sufficiency as soon
as possible, the Pakistani government has been providing new
impetus to agriculture, which accounts for about 25 percent of the
country's gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
The government led by Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif has announced
some new agricultural policies since it came to power in February
last year, under which import tariff on plants and machinery meant
for agricultural use is removed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, land for agricultural use will be leased to foreign
companies for 30 years, extendable for a further period of 20
years. And no ceiling has been imposed on land for registered
agricultural companies.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to encourage farmers to improve the output of
various crops, the government will increase support prices for
agricultural products and secure easy and enhanced supply of
credit, availability of better-quality seeds and adequate supply
of fertilizers and unadulterated pesticides.
</P>
<P>
Supply of water for irrigation will also be improved and funds
for farming machines and extension services will be sufficient.
</P>
<P>
As an agricultural country, Pakistan was food self-sufficient
in the 1980s and was even called "the barn of South Asia."
However, the performance of its agriculture has been disappointing
in the past few years and the country now has to import food every
year to meet domestic needs.
</P>
<P>
During the 1996-97 fiscal year, Pakistan's economy declined to
the lowest level in its history and agriculture was the
worst-affected sector, which recorded a growth rate of less than 1
percent compared with 5.3 percent in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The low growth rate of agriculture was the result of a
4.5-percent decline in the production of all major crops except
rice, which fortunately reached a record level of 4.31 million
tons as against 3.96 million tons a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Shortage of food items like flour and sugar occurred during
1996-97, due partly to a sizable decline in their production and
partly to the failure of the authorities concerned to foresee the
situation and thus avert it by arranging adequate stock.
</P>
<P>
In the current season, the sowing of wheat has been delayed due
to lack of planning by the authorities concerned in some flood-
and rain-hit areas.
</P>
<P>
But the government is still expecting a bumper harvest as the
area under wheat has increased this year by 28,329 hectares to
623,229 hectares thanks to the provision of credits to small
farmers by the government.
</P>
<P>
Even if the wheat harvest in 1998 reaches the projected 19
million tons, the country will still have to import about 3
million tons at a cost of about 500 million dollars to meet
demand. And the government has approved the import of 4 million
tons.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the production of rice looks promising and is
expected to be around 4.6 million tons.
</P>
<P>
For the last 10 years, Pakistan has been importing more and
more wheat, from 600,000 tons in 1987-88 to 4 million tons in
1996-97.
</P>
<P>
According to Sattar Lalika, minister for food and agriculture,
the Agricultural Development Bank of Pakistan has disbursed 9.057
billion rupees (about 206 million U.S. dollars) to farmers in the
first half of the current fiscal year starting from July 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
In compliance with the instruction of Prime Minister Sharif to
"grow more wheat," the bank has reportedly drawn up a credit plan
to help farmers maximize wheat production.
</P>
<P>
Declaring the year of 1998 as the "wheat year," the Pakistani
government is striving to achieve food self-sufficiency next year.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
