<HEADLINE> Rival Cypriots Exchange Info on Missing Persons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, January 23 (Xinhua) -- The Greek Cypriot and Turkish
Cypriot representatives on the divided Cyprus island met here
Friday to exchange information on the location of graves of
missing persons.
</P>
<P>
Under the U.N. auspices, the meeting between Greek Cypriot
representative Takis Christofpoulos and Turkish Cypriot
representative Rustem Tatar took place at the Ledra Palace Hotel
situated in the U.N.-controlled buffer zone in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time the two sides exchanged information on
missing persons in a bid to make headway in resolving this
humanitarian issue, which constitutes a main aspect of the Cyprus
problem.
</P>
<P>
In a brief statement to reporters after the 45-minute-long
meeting, U.N. Resident Representative in Cyprus Gustave Feissel
said the meeting is the implementation of an agreement signed on
July 31, 1997 by Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides and Turkish
Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash.
</P>
<P>
The agreement stipulates that "the two leaders agree to
provide each other immediately and simultaneously all information
already at their disposal on the location of graves of Greek
Cypriot and Turkish Cypriot missing persons."
</P>
<P>
Feissel also noted that the two sides "agreed to meet again
soon to discuss the preparation of arrangements leading to the
return of the remains of the Greek Cypriot and Turkish Cypriot
missing persons in question."
</P>
<P>
Christopoulos described the meeting as "important" as it is
the beginning of the implementation of the July agreement.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Tatar said "I think both sides are sincere and we
will proceed."
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the Greek Cypriot side handed over
information on 200 Turkish Cypriots missing cases and the Turkish
Cypriot side disclosed information about 400 missing Greek
Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into Greek Cypriot-controlled south and
Turkish Cypriot-nominated north since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island following a
failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1,619 Greek Cypriots and Greeks were listed as
missing after the 1974 Turkish invasion. The Turkish Cypriot side
listed some 500 as missing since communal clashes erupted on the
island in 1963. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
