<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Situation Returns to Normal in Harare </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Situation in Harare city center
returned to normal today following three-days of food riots that
disrupted business in the capital.
</P>
<P>
The city was calm with most commercial enterprises which
include banks and shops operating as usual.
</P>
<P>
However, the police still maintained a huge presence at
strategic points and sites which were looted during the riots
that went on from Monday to Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The riots were sparked by recent price hikes of commodities by
an average 20 percent. The International Socialist Organization
claimed to be behind the riots.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government said in a statement on Friday that
there had been no deaths or shootings since the deployment of
soldiers to help police restore law and order.
</P>
<P>
A weekly "Independent" paper said the riots claimed eight
lives.
</P>
<P>
The government said the deployment of soldiers and police in
areas affected by riots had helped bring back the situation to
normal.
</P>
<P>
Most shops, schools, colleges and businesses in the capital
which had closed during the riots were now open as a result of
the security measures, it said.
</P>
<P>
The statement said, " Anyone receiving threats to close
business should remain calm, continue operating and report such
threats to the police in their areas. The defense forces will
remain deployed until the situation normalizes to their
satisfaction." The statement said 2,300 arrests had so far been
made. 
</P>
</TEXT>
