<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Re-commits to Expanding Settlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu reaffirmed Friday his commitment to continuing
building the Har Homa settlement in Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu gave the assurance during his meeting with hardline
Jerusalem Mayor Ehud Olmert Friday morning. He said tenders would
be issued without delay to begin building about 6,500 housing
units in Har Homa.
</P>
<P>
He was apparently trying to allay mounting concerns by
right-wing hardliners who fear that the government would stop the
Har Homa construction under strong U.S. pressure.
</P>
<P>
The controversial Har Homa project last March sparked
widespread protests and condemnation from the Palestinians and the
Arab world, virtually bringing the Israeli-Palestinian peace
process to a halt.
</P>
<P>
Following almost one-year non-stop building, workers have
completed the first-stage construction of infrastructure work,
paving roads and laying pipelines. But tenders have not been
issued for beginning the genuine construction of the housing
units.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government has been pressuring Israel to have a
"time-out" the work in Har Homa and other settlements as a
goodwill gesture to the Palestinians in a bid to advancing the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
A group of rightist activists recently tried to bring a convoy
of construction vehicles to the site in Har Homa to demand for
accelerating the work. After being prevented from reaching the
site, they have been planning to gather several hundred supporters
for another major demonstration later this month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
