<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Leaders of CBSS Adhere to Regional Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 23 (Xinhua) -- The heads of the governments
from 11 nations in the Council of Baltic Sea States (CBSS) today
ended the two-day second summit with a declaration, the Interfax
news agency reported from Riga, Latvia, on Friday.
</P>
<P>
In the declaration the prime ministers confirmed their
adherence to regional cooperation, thinking that will enhance the
formation of a stable, democratic and prosperous Europe without
dividing lines.
</P>
<P>
The declaration says they welcomed the Luxembourg meeting of
the European Union which had made a decision to start the
preparations for the inclusion of Latvia, Lithuania, Poland and
Estonia, as well as the coming into force of a Partnership and
Cooperation Agreement between Russia and the European Union.
</P>
<P>
The declaration emphasized the importance of fighting organized
crime and illegal migration and called for the signing of
appropriate agreements between countries of the region.
</P>
<P>
The conference of the Council supports the early joining of
Latvia, Lithuania, Russia and Estonia to the World Trade
Organization, regarding it as an important contribution to
economic cooperation and attraction of new investments in the
region, the declaration says.
</P>
<P>
The 11 prime ministers called on the Council to keep the member
nations posted on the expansion of the European Union and on
cooperation with Russia.
</P>
<P>
The leaders emphasized the need to cooperate with Poland,
Russia and the former Soviet republics on the southern Baltic
coast in planning regional cooperation projects.
</P>
<P>
The CBSS was founded in 1992, and its first summit was held in
Wisby, Sweden, in May 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
