<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Blasts Arafat's Letter on Covenant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Israel blasted Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat Friday for playing "tactic" by presenting
U.S. President Bill Clinton a letter assuring that the
Palestinian Covenant has been revised.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, who is in Washington for meetings with Clinton, gave
the letter to the U.S. president on Thursday, specifying the
provisions of the charter calling for Israel's destruction have
been annulled by the Palestinian National Council in April 1996.
</P>
<P>
David Bar-Illan, media adviser to Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu, said the letter was not enough, adding the
Palestinian side in fact has not genuinely revised the charter,
because only the convening of the Palestinian National Council
could do it.
</P>
<P>
"The letter presented by Chairman Arafat to President Clinton
about the Palestinian Covenant is, I'm afraid, another exercise
of evasion," Bar-Illan said in an interview with Israeli state
television Channel I.
</P>
<P>
"The only way the Palestinian Covenant can be repealed or
changed is through convening of the Palestinian National Council,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
He said that Israel is not asking the Palestinian side to draft
a new charter but only to remove the articles calling for
destroying Israel. Israel has been listing the revision of
Palestinian Covenant as a precondition for carrying out the
long-delayed second redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Britain, which is holding the rotating president of the
European Union, on Friday expressed support to the Palestinian
side by attacking Israel for creating new hurdle to the peace
process on the covenant issue.
</P>
<P>
British Foreign Office Minister Derek Fatchett said in London
that Britain regarded Arafat's assurance was sufficient, judging
by the letter on the covenant sent to British Prime Minister Tony
Blair recently by Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Fatchett, who visited Israel and the Palestinian self-rule
territories last week, said it was not sensible for Israel to keep
making demand on the covenant issue.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, commenting on Netanyahu's meetings with Clinton in
Washington this week, Israeli Cabinet Secretary Danny Naveh said
the U.S. has not changed its position that it is up to Israel to
define the scope of further redeployments.
</P>
<P>
He said Netanyahu has presented Clinton with Israeli positions
that further redeployment would only be carried out without
harming Israeli national interests and on condition that the
Palestinian side fulfills its commitments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
