<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Price Slide Spells Pain for Oil Producers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Abu Dhabi, January 23 (Xinhua) -- The slide in world oil prices
could spark a financial crisis for many members of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC), which have
based their budgets on higher prices.
</P>
<P>
According to an economic newsletter here Friday, oil producers
"will have to come to grips with the unpleasant prospect that the
current oil price slide could, in the absence of prompt action to
restrain supply, turn into something a good deal more serious than
a temporary downturn."
</P>
<P>
The Middle East Economic Survey said "if that were to be the
case, the financial pain of such an eventuality would well be
traumatic."
</P>
<P>
Since reaching a high point of around 21 U.S. dollars a barrel
in October last year, world oil prices have tumbled to some 15
dollars a barrel this month.
</P>
<P>
"At these levels, prices are well below the reference oil
values employed for the 1998 budgets of a number of key OPEC
countries which are likely to find themselves in a grave financial
trouble if the present situation persists or deteriorates," said
the newsletter.
</P>
<P>
It cited the Iranian budget, which was based on an assumed oil
price of 17.50 dollars a barrel and forecast an estimated total
revenue of 17.46 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Iran has now cut its oil price base to 16 dollars a barrel, the
newsletter said. The level was still higher than current prices for
Iranian crude.
</P>
<P>
The newsletter said it appeared that OPEC had "probably
overstepped the mark" with its November decision to raise the
output ceiling to 27.5 million barrels per day (bpd) from 25.03
million bpd.
</P>
<P>
The decision had failed to curb output from those producing
above their quotas and unleashed additional volume from those who
had been producing below quota but had spare capacity to meet the
new levels, the newsletter added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
