<HEADLINE> Trial of S. African Ex-President Postponed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 23 (Xinhua) -- The trial of former South
African president P. W. Botha for his failure to testify before
the Truth and Reconciliation Commission (TRC) has been postponed
to February 23.
</P>
<P>
About 400 African National Congress (ANC) demonstrators and
some 20 supporters of Botha gathered outside the George Regional
Court in Western Cape this morning when the 82-year-old former
National Party (NP) leader arrived for court hearing.
</P>
<P>
Botha was summoned to appear in court earlier this month for
ignoring a third subpoena from the TRC last month to appear in
its hearing on former State Security Council, of which Botha was
in charge in height of the Apartheid.
</P>
<P>
After a brief court hearing of only 22 minutes, Botha told a
press conference that he stood by all those who had executed
"lawful commands" from the former government led by him in its
struggle against the "revolutionary communist onslaught against
our country".
</P>
<P>
During his 11 years in power, as prime minister from 1978 to
1984 and then state president until 1989, Botha enacted emergency
laws to crack down on anti-apartheid groups.
</P>
<P>
He said the TRC seems to have "ignored and forgotten" that
"onslaught", which was conducted "in all avenues of life and
consisted of the most violent acts against the civilians of our
country".
</P>
<P>
He said he was not prepared to apologize for his government's
"lawful actions" to curb the "violent onslaught".
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the white-based parties, the Freedom Front and the
Conservative Party, and some members of the former NP cabinet
were present in the court.
</P>
<P>
If Botha pleads not guilty in the February 23 hearing, the
case will go to trial on April 14. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
