<HEADLINE> African Leaders' Forum Opens in Kampala </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, January 23 (Xinhua) -- The forum of east and
southern African leaders on peace, stability and development
cooperation in Africa opened here on Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
The closed-door meeting for 12 African state and government
leaders will focus on the subjects including investing in
infrastructure, promoting regional integration, trade and private
investment, using and building human and institutional capacity,
conflict prevention and post conflict reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is chaired by Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
and World Bank President James Wolfenson who arrived here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The other African leaders attending the two-dayouth Africa and
Zambia.
</P>
<P>
The participants of the summit represent 47 percent of the
population of sub-Saharan Africa, 50 percent of the continent's
exports and 60 percent of its gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
The countries sending representatives to the meeting
received 53 percent of Africa's official development assistance.
</P>
<P>
Issaias Afwerki, the president of Eritrea, did not come today
as scheduled. 
</P>
</TEXT>
