<HEADLINE> Namibia, Botswana Fail to Reach Pact on Troop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Namibia and Botswana have
failed to reach an agreement on Botswanan troops' withdrawal from
a disputed island in the Caprivi region, sources reaching here
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
However, a meeting of the Namibia-Botswana Joint Commission,
established for settlement of the border dispute, has proposed
that the two countries set up a joint technical body to look into
the demarcation of boundaries.
</P>
<P>
The meeting at Katima Mulilo, provincial capital of Namibia's
northeastern province of Caprivi, agreed that the technical body
would be set up in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
It was also agreed that Namibian villagers cultivating fields
on Situngu Island be allowed to continue, irrespective of the
technical body, the Namibian Broadcasting Corporation reported.
</P>
<P>
Botswana Minister of Presidential Affairs, Ponatshego
Kedikilwe, assured farmers on the island that Botswana troops
will not harass them.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that Botswana soldiers had occupied Situngo
Island and had harassed Namibian farmers who had crops planted
there.
</P>
<P>
Last week the Namibian government urged people of the country
to "remain calm and refrain from taking unwise steps" before the
Situngu Island dispute with Botswana was resolved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
