<HEADLINE> UAE Expects 5.5 Percent GDP Growth in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, January 23 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates
(UAE) planning minister expected the country's 1998 gross domestic
product growth at about 5.5 percent due to its increased oil
output.
</P>
<P>
According to local press Friday, Sheikh Humaid bin Ahmad al
Mualla said "I project the 5.5 percent growth rate in 1998 on the
back of our increased oil production under the new OPEC
(Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries) ceiling."
</P>
<P>
UAE was allocated a 2.336 million barrels per day (bpd)
production quota at the Jakarta OPEC meeting in December from a
previous 2.161 million bpd.
</P>
<P>
The new UAE quota was part of an overall increase in OPEC's
production with its ceiling now topping 27.5 million bpd.
</P>
<P>
The new ceiling triggered a price crisis in wold oil
market. This month prices tumbled by 3 dollars to around 15
dollars a barrel, the lowest level since mid-1994.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Humaid said he expected things to change in next few
months "as a result of increased oil sales despite the current
signs of weakness." 
</P>
</TEXT>
