<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Dismiss Israeli Withdrawal Offer as "Peanuts" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasir
Arafat on Friday blasted Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu's very limited pullback from the West Bank, describing
it as unacceptable peanuts.
</P>
<P>
"What he is offering is peanuts. It cannot be accepted," Arafat
told a news conference before he leaves Washington after winding
up talks with U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu offered a very modest pullback during his talks with
Clinton on Tuesday and it was said the size he agreed to cede to
the Palestinians was under 10 percent of the occupied land of the
West Bank. And even this unsignificant withdrawal he said would
not be carried out until he was satisfied with security measures
to be taken by the Palestinian Authority.
</P>
<P>
But Arafat demanded that 60 percent of the territories should
be turned over by the Israelis, apart from 27 percent already
under the control of the Palestinian Authority.
</P>
<P>
When asked about two sessions of talks with Clinton, Arafat
said they were "successful, important and positive." He also
thanked Clinton for his mediation efforts and said he hoped to
"break the deadlock" of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration is trying to revitalize the stymied
peace process in the Middle East, telling the Israeli and
Palestinian leaders that "we need some results soon."
</P>
<P>
The next move probably will be talks in Europe between
Netanyahu and Arafat brokered by Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright. And at that trilateral meeting, Albright would again try
to convince the Israeli and Palestinian leader to accept a Clinton
formula for the settlement of differences between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Albright said on Thursday at a news conference that Clinton had
decided on a strategy of urging a phased Israeli troop withdrawal
timed to Palestinian actions against terrorism.
</P>
<P>
"We've introduced the concept of parallel processes of
implementation of these commitments," she told reporters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
