<HEADLINE> Kagame's proposal to End Prisons' Burden </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Rwandan Vice-president, Major
General paul Kagame has come up with a proposal to solve the
burden imposed on the government by the big number of genocide
suspects crammed in the country's prisons.
</P>
<P>
While addressing the Rwandan community in Belgium Wednesday,
Kagame who doubles as Defense Minister, said it is a challenging
task for the government to continue to feed genocide suspects, a
report from the Rwandan News Agency in Kigali sent to Xinhua here
Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Rwandan prisons accommodate over 100,000 genocide suspects
today," Kagame pointed out.
</P>
<P>
"On them, we cannot continue to shoulder this burden and
organizations assisting us are getting wary," he emphasised.
</P>
<P>
The personal proposal to urgently get out of this crisis put
forth by General Kagame would be to identify notorious criminals,
the masterminds, and to trial and execute them in public.
</P>
<P>
The criminals of the second category, notably the executioners
of the plan of extermination of Tutsis, would be also identified
and confined to an area where they can be subjected to public
works.
</P>
<P>
Other criminals, including those who were instigated to commit
massacres would be handed to traditional courts that would handle
their cases.
</P>
<P>
This proposal will be submitted to Rwandans for a popular
prescript, he underscored, but did not say when. 
</P>
</TEXT>
