<HEADLINE> French Extreme-Right Promotes Selective Family Aid Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 23 (Xinhua) -- The French extreme-right National
Front (FN) party is promoting a selective family aid policy by
creating an aid exclusively for French and European families with
new-born babies in an FN-administered city.
</P>
<P>
The FN decision is immediately condemned by government,
non-governmental groups and both left and right politicians as a
"discriminatory" measure aimed at luring votes in the
forthcoming regional and cantonal elections to be held in March.
</P>
<P>
A free-masons group Friday said the FN decision is
unconstitutional and violates the rule of the European Union,
while the Minister of Justice Martine Aubry called it "shocking"
and "shameful."
</P>
<P>
Calling the policy as one of "national preference," the FN
announced on Thursday that the southern city of Vitrolles will
provide the families with new born-babies but having at least one
French or western European father or mother 5,000 francs (830 U.S.
dollars) of family aid.
</P>
<P>
Vitrolles is run by Catherine Bruno, an FN politician, whose
husband is the number two of the party Megret Bruno.
</P>
<P>
The FN also proposed Friday to extend the policy to the Central
region of France, if FN candidates are elected in regional
elections there.
</P>
<P>
The FN president Jean-Marie Le Pen said Friday that he has long
hoped that the policy should be adopted by FN-run cities, and said
that it is based on the principle of his party that French money
should be used for French families.
</P>
<P>
"It is the French families who need to have many children, not
foreign families," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
