<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Self-Reliance Urged in Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ARUSHA, Tanzania, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian Prime
Minister Fredrich Sumaye today urged African countries to enhance
their capability to prevent and resolve conflicts instead of
waiting for outside interference.
</P>
<P>
Sumaye was speaking on behalf of President Benjamin Mkapa at
the closing here of an international workshop on African Conflict
resolution.
</P>
<P>
"The majority of present conflicts on our continent are
essentially of our own making -- whether internally within one
country, or across African borders. Hence their solution will be
realized to a large extent by focusing on the domestic or
regional scene," said Sumaye.
</P>
<P>
"Africans cannot today abdicate responsibility for the
conflicts in or between their countries," the prime minister
noted.
</P>
<P>
"Today very few conflicts can fully and justifiably be
explained in terms of extra Africa interference in African
affairs. And after 40 years of independence, we can only have
ourselves to blame if we continue to be influenced by the legacy
of colonialism."
</P>
<P>
Sumaye said peace initiatives undertaken by African bodies
like the Organization of African Unity have been successful at
various levels.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, what is really important is the fact that at
last Africa is taking charge and responsibility for its conflicts
and their resolution.
</P>
<P>
He called for regional solutions and mechanism for conflict
prevention, management and resolution.
</P>
<P>
"Finding regional solutions to regional conflicts is an
especially important strategy in dealing with African conflicts.
At the regional level we understand each other better -- sharing,
as we do history, cultural values and temperaments.
</P>
<P>
"It is easier for regional leaders to sit down together and
hammer out solutions anchored in the region and supported by our
continental body and the international community at large," he
said.
</P>
<P>
But he cautioned that such solutions should not infringe upon
the territorial integrity of a country or countries involved in a
conflict.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized a concerted regional stance on regional
conflicts.
</P>
<P>
"In addition there is the question of developing the capacity
to monitor, evaluate and coordinate the implementation of agreed
solutions to regional conflicts.
</P>
<P>
"This remains a great weakness."
</P>
<P>
The prime minister called for the elimination of
"misconceptions" of rights and duties of individual citizenry or
of individual nations.
</P>
<P>
"There are cases where one ethnic group thinks it has the
right -- even birth right -- to rule because of reasons of
history or of numerical size," he said, apparently referring to
the tribal clashes in the Great Lakes region.
</P>
<P>
"This of course, is not the essence of liberty and such people
need to be disabused of these notions."
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that many conflicts in Africa arose out of
these misconceptions or misplaced expectations and called for
good governance and the establishment of democracy in African
countries.
</P>
<P>
He believed that the causes of conflicts were multi-faceted
but the most important cause is the pursuit of social, political
and economic ambitions through unfair means.
</P>
<P>
"We often attribute conflicts to ethnic, racial, historical,
religious, economic and cultural factors. But these factors,
causative as they may appear, do not sufficiently explain why
some conflicts are more intractable than others, or why they
occur in some places and not in others.
</P>
<P>
"Not infrequently these factors are used only as smoke-screens
behind which socio-political and economic ambitions are pursued
often in the most undemocratic and unacceptable manner."
</P>
<P>
The three-day workshop, which was joinly organized by the
Tanzanian Foreign Ministry and the Mwalimu Nyerere Foundation,
attracted some 200 diplomats, peace-makers, scholars, and
officials from international and regional organizations and
non-governmental organizations.
</P>
<P>
The participants exchanged experiences and lessons in conflict
mediation and discussed the role of civil society and women in
peace-making processes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980124.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-23 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oman Launches Campaign Against Expatriate Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Oman has begun to implement a
program to increase the size of indigenous workforce in 1998, the
Omani news agency monitored here said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Omanization campaign was launched earlier this month under
Oman's Sultan Qaboos Bin Said's order of providing employment to
at least one member of each Omani household, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
Oman's new Minister of Social Affair and Labor Sheikh Amrer bin
Shuwain al Hosni said his ministry had "immediately started
implementing the royal directive" with priority for jobs being
given to member of Omani families receiving social security
benefits.
</P>
<P>
He said his ministry has issued new rules and procedures
permitting the recruitment of foreign labor only for companies
involved in trading and contracting.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Amrer said the aim of the campaign, which was considered
too aggressive by some economic experts, was to limit expatriate
labor strictly to the requirements of the labor markets.
</P>
<P>
Private sector was the first to be involved in the campaign.
Sheikh Amrer said the Omani government wants to increase the
number of Omanis in the private sector to 350,000 by the year 2000
from the current 250,000.
</P>
<P>
Oman currently employed 500,000 foreigners in government and
private sectors.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said before the launch of the move that Oman has
warned illegal foreign workers to leave by March 31 or face
penalties.
</P>
<P>
Oman is the sixth and the last Gulf Arab state to deport
illegal expatriate workers. The United Arab Emirates led the
expulsion campaign in the region in 1994 and was followed by Saudi
Arabia, Bahrain, Kuwait and Qatar.
</P>
<P>
The campaign to flush out illegal foreign labors was prompted
by a high unemployment rate among the six Gulf Arab states, which
was estimated at more than 15 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
