<HEADLINE> S. Africa Denies Involvement in Violating Angolan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, January 23 (Xinhua) -- The South African government
Friday denies any involvement in the January 20 incident which
has violated Angola's air space.
</P>
<P>
A South African private airplane was forced down Tuesday near
Menongue, a city in southwestern Angola by the Angolan air force
for transporting cargo for the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA).
</P>
<P>
Reddy Manpane, South African ambassador in Angola, read to the
press here Friday the declaration by its government, which
expresses its worries over the incident which has violated the
U.N. Security Council resolution to impose air embargo on UNITA,
pledging its support for the resolution made for peace in Angola.
</P>
<P>
According to the declaration, the South African government
will take stricter measures to safeguard the implementation of
the U.N. resolution, adding that such incidents should be
seriously dealt with by both the United Nations and countries in
the region.
</P>
<P>
With regard to whether South Africa could exert control on its
private aviation companies, Manpane said it is difficult to
control all the planes since there are altogether 263 airports in
the country.
</P>
<P>
Some of the planes apply to fly to Botswana, but turn out to
end in Angola or the Democratic Republic of Congo, which is
difficult to manage, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Manpane believed that all planes violating Angola's space must
be punished and that the eight people detained on the plane
should be responsible for their crime.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary investigation show that the DC-4 plane is a
private South African plane grounded on its way to the central
Angolan city of Ondulo to transport cargos for the former rebel
movement UNITA.
</P>
<P>
Seven of the eight people on board are from South Africa, the
other one is from Congo (K).
</P>
<P>
Currently the case is under investigation by Angola's Ministry
of Internal Affairs. 
</P>
