<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Football Referee May Be Wrong Sometimes: Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Criticisms of football referees'
eyesight by fans may contain a grain of scientific truth
sometimes, according to a study published today.
</P>
<P>
Researchers from Spain have discovered that because of the way
the eye focuses, the eye of the assistant referee, formerly known
as the linesman, sometimes cannot keep pace with the feet of a
footballer.
</P>
<P>
Dr Jaime Sanabria and his colleagues, from the Fundacion
Jimenez Diaz in Madrid, looked at the problem with the help of a
referee from the Spanish Royal Football Federation.
</P>
<P>
Writing in the medical journal Lancet, they said that the
assistant referee has "an erroneous image of the initial positions
of the players at the exact moment the pass of the ball began."
</P>
<P>
The off-side rule requires the assistant referee to judge where
the attacker was at the exact moment when the ball was passed to
him by one of his own side.
</P>
<P>
But researchers found that eye takes 250-300 milliseconds to
focus an image on the tiny spot in the center of retina known as
the fovea which "sees" best.
</P>
<P>
In that time, an attacker and defender who started in the same
horizontal line on the pitch can be as much as 4.5 meters apart.
</P>
<P>
The result is that the referee will "see" an attacker and
defender running apart when, in fact, they are level. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980124.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Set to Fight Dynamite Fishing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 23 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian government
is planning a fresh attack on illegal fishing with explosives in
Dar es Salaam.
</P>
<P>
The Minister for Natural Resources and Tourism, Zakia Meghji,
said her ministry is investigating allegations that blast sounds
are heard by residents between 8 am and 2 pm every day in the
Magogoni Ferry and Mji Mwema of the city here, according to a
report from the Guard paper.
</P>
<P>
Meghiji said dynamite fishing is prohibited in the Indian
Ocean and all lakes of the country. A campaign to battle dynamite
fishing since July 1 last year has been going on well.
</P>
<P>
For example, she said, dynamite fishing in the Kunduchi area
in Dar es Salaam, which also scared tourists, has been put under
control.
</P>
<P>
Between July and November last year, the Tanzanian police and
Tanzania People's Defense Forces (TPDF) arrested 102 suspects and
impounded seven tons of fish in Dar es Salaam, Coast and Tanga
regions. During the crackdown, 45 gas cylinders, three outboard
engine boats and 10 canoes were confiscated.
</P>
<P>
The minister told the newspaper that 23 million shillings
(about 36,000 U.S. Dollars) have been put aside for the ministry
and the TPDF to battle dynamite fishing specially.
</P>
<P>
Meghji, however, said that lack of modern facilities such as
patrol boats have weakened the campaign. The ministry is looking
into the possibility of acquiring a modern boat, she added.
</P>
</TEXT>
