<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lewinsky's Attorney Criticizes Investigator </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Former White House intern
Monica Lewinsky's attorney said today U.S. independent counsel
Kenneth Starr's investigation of his client "squeezed" Lewinsky to
get information about her alleged sexual affair with President
Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
"I don't like the way the investigation has been conducted,"
William Ginsburg told ABC's "Good Morning America." "Repeatedly
during discussions with the office of the prosecutor we have been
squeezed."
</P>
<P>
"They've even made threats to involve her parents who, as far
as I know, know nothing about the situation," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ginsburg's criticism came a day after Starr defended
controversial techniques used in the case, reported to have
included hidden devices to record a conversation Lewinsky had with
Linda Tripp, her former colleague in whom she had confided.
</P>
<P>
Ginsburg complained about Starr's method for questioning
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
"Right off the bat we talk about stings and wires and traps,"
Ginsburg said. "I'm not happy with that at all, especially when
you're dealing with a 24-year-old girl. It's not nice."
</P>
<P>
He said Starr, apparently after receiving tapes of Tripp's wire
conversations with Lewinsky, "lured" his client to a hotel in
Northern Virginia and questioned her for hours without an attorney
being present.
</P>
<P>
"That should frighten anyone who is involved in the process
here in America.... That's very, very sad, isn't it? They did not
give her permission to call her attorney and I wasn't there."
</P>
<P>
Ginsburg also called on Starr to allow him to listen to the
tapes of the conversation between his client and Tripp.
</P>
<P>
"I haven't heard those tapes, I don't have the information that
the press has. I have heard quotes from the tapes. I wonder why
the office of the independent counsel won't let me listen to the
tapes and comment on them?"
</P>
<P>
Ginsburg, citing attorney-client confidentiality, would not
comment directly on whether or not Lewinsky had a sexual affair
with Clinton as has been alleged.
</P>
<P>
Ginsburg said Lewinsky and Clinton had, as far as he knew, only
a working relationship with the president.
</P>
<P>
He also denied comment on reports that Clinton's friend Vernon
Jordan tried to get Lewinsky to lie about the alleged affair that
was said to have begun in 1995 when she was 21.
</P>
<P>
Lewinsky was originally scheduled to give a deposition today in
the Paula Jones sexual harassment case against the president, but
U.S. District Judge Susan Webber Wright postponed it indefinitely
late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Lewinsky's attorney had indicated earlier that he would seek to
postpone his client's deposition. Lewinsky previously submitted an
affidavit in the case and denied any affair with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
USA Today reported today that Lewinsky said in her affidavit,
"I have the utmost respect for the president, who always behaved
appropriately in my presence. I have never had a sexual
relationship with the president."
</P>
<P>
On Thursday Clinton continued to deny allegations of an affair,
saying, "The allegations are false, and I would never ask anybody
to do anything other than tell the truth." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980124.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US: Iraq's Position on Arms Inspection Unacceptable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Iraq's position on the
issue of the arms inspection is unacceptable, Bill Richardson,
ambassador of the United States to the United Nations, said here
today.
</P>
<P>
Richardson made the remarks after Richard Butler, the executive
chairman of the United Nations Special Commission (UNSCOM) in
charge of dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass destruction, briefed
the Security Council on his latest visit to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"The report is deeply disturbing, deeply negative and
unacceptable. The United States feels very strongly that there
should be full and unfetered access to all sites," Richardson told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
"Iraq's response can be described in one word: `defiance,'
defiance of the Security Council's resolutions, defiance of UN
arms teams and defiance of the international community. Thus we
find it unacceptable," he said.
</P>
<P>
"In the next few days, we will consult with our allies on the
next steps. We want to resolve the issues diplomatically, but we
will not rule any option out," he added.
</P>
<P>
Butler visited Iraq from January 19-21 when he held three
rounds of talks with Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tareq Aziz. Their
talks yielded no progress on the issues of arms inspection.
</P>
</TEXT>
