<DOCNO> XIE19980124.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> E.U. Envoy to Start Shuttle Diplomacy on Burundi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ARUSHA, Tanzania, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Aldo Ajello, European
Union envoy for the Great Lakes region, will meet with Ugandan
President Yoweri Museveni and Ethiopian Premier Meles Zenawi next
week on how to speed up the peace process in Burundi.
</P>
<P>
Ajello disclosed the news to Xinhua on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
After exchanging views on the issue with the Burundi Foreign
Minister during a three-day international workshop on African
resolutions to!conflicts ending here Friday, he noted that the
date of this year's regional summit on Burundi is yet to be
fixed.
</P>
<P>
"The Burundi peace process is on the track," the envoy said,
adding that leaders in the Great Lakes region are making efforts
to bring all parties inside the tiny central African country to
the negotiations table as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Issues like constitution, army and judicial systems are
expected to be high on the agenda at the negotiations which are
much likely to open this year, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Ajello said the sanctions imposed by the Great
Lakes nations on Burundi were reduced sharply throughout last
year, implying that once the negotiations start, the regional
leaders would finally officially lift the one-and-a-half-year
ban.
</P>
<P>
"The sanctions are never against (Burundi President Pierre)
Buyoya personally," he claimed, adding the ban is always aimed at
pressing all the parties involved to start dialogue and
negotiations which may lead to the establishment of a government
of transition.
</P>
<P>
Buyoya took power in a coup in 1996, three years after the
civil war was sparked by the murder of the country's first
president Melchior Ndadaye, which claimed about 150,000 lives
since.
</P>
<P>
"I don't believe very strongly in sanctions from which it is
the people who suffer, not the regime," he added.
</P>
<P>
He also spoke highly of the increasing ability and flexibility
of African countries to deal with their own problems through
joint efforts by various regional peace-broking mechanisms under
the Organization of African Unity.
</P>
<P>
"We (the EU) are encouraged by African countries' efforts to
find their own solutions to their own problems," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The western countries are not prepared anymore to intervene
in African affairs. They don't want to spend money or risk their
lives," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
