<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistani Sentenced to Death for Killing CIA Men </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 23 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. judge sentenced a
Pakistani citizen to death today for killing two Central
Intelligence Agency (CIA) employees outside CIA headquarters near
Washington five years ago.
</P>
<P>
Mir Aimal Kasi, 33, opened an assault rifle at motorists stuck
in morning rush hour traffic on January 25, 1993, killing CIA
communications worker Frank Darling, 28, and CIA analyst and
physician Lansing Bennett, 66.
</P>
<P>
Circuit Court Judge J. Howe Brown, speaking in the heavily
guarded courthouse in Fairfax County, 20 miles (32 km) west of
Washington, said he accepted the jury's recommendation that Kasi
be executed for the shooting spree on January 25, 1993.
</P>
<P>
The six-man, six-woman jury that convicted Kasi of capital
murder in November had recommended the death penalty. In Virginia,
judges have the final say on sentencing but rarely depart from a
jury's decision.
</P>
<P>
Kasi, who was captured last June in Pakistan after four years'
run and brought to the United States for trial, told the court
that his action was a retaliation for U.S. policies that he said
hurt Islamic nations.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Fairfax Circuit Court Judge J. Howe Brown, Kasi
reiterated his political motives. "This is the result of a wrong
policy toward Muslim countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said he did not expect any mercy from the court or from the
United States. "I don't expect any justice or mercy from your
country or this court," Kasi said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
