<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, January 24 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraq said Saturday that it will drop the quota
system of oil products including gasoline and gas to citizens
which was introduced last November in preparation for a possible
U.S. military action.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made at a Cabinet meeting under President
Saddam Hussein here, the Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Iraq introduced the quota system following the standoff between
Iraq and the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) on removal of the
Iraqi mass destruction weapons.
</P>
<P>
Iraq expelled U.S. members of the U.N. inspection teams, saying
they were spies, while Washington threatened military action. The
tension was eased after Russian mediation. (Iraq-Oil-Sales)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- Pakistan is considering the proposals sent by
India to operationalize the mechanism of addressing all the
outstanding issues including Kashmir between the two countries, a
Foreign Office spokesman said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a weekly press briefing here, the spokesman said
that "we have received some proposals from India which deserve
thorough consideration." However, he did not elaborate the
proposals.
</P>
<P>
He said non-operalization of the agreed mechanism is the main
hurdle to the resumption of talks. (Pakistan-India-Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Leaders from 11 Baltic Sea countries conducted a
summit on Friday in Riga, capital of Latvia, discussing regional
economic cooperation, crime-fighting and the European Union
enlargement.
</P>
<P>
The leaders, present at the second Council of the Baltic Sea
States (CBSS), also discussed energy issue and agreed to create an
integrated gas market and power network in the region.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed to hold an energy ministerial meeting in Oslo,
Norway, soon to further discuss the matter.
</P>
<P>
Further, they called on international financial institutions to
enhance their investment in the Baltic Sea States, and expressed
willingness to improve investment environment in their own
countries. (Baltic-Summit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- Four more private banks in Indonesia are merging in
a bid to strengthen their operation capacity, the Antara News
Agency reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The four banks, namely Bank Umum Nasional, Bank Bukopin, Bank
Tugu and Bank Duta, signed a Memorandum of Understanding on the
merger here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Managing Director of Bank Duta Muchtar Mandala said after the
signing ceremony that the merged bank could become reality in late
 June 1998, and will have combined assets of 21.2 trillion rupiah
(one U.S. dollar equals 12,000 rupiah now) and total equity of
1.395 trillion rupiah. (Indonesia-Banks) 
</P>
</TEXT>
