<HEADLINE> Iraq Deregulates Domestic Oil Sale </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Iraq said Saturday that it will
drop the quota system of oil products including gasoline and gas
to citizens which was introduced last November in preparation for
a possible U.S. military action.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made at a Cabinet meeting under President
Saddam Hussein here, the Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Iraq introduced the quota system following the standoff between
Iraq and the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) on removal of the
Iraqi mass destruction weapons.
</P>
<P>
Iraq expelled U.S. members of the U.N. inspection teams, saying
they were spies, while Washington threatened military action. The
tension was eased after Russian mediation.
</P>
<P>
Iraq said the quota system was part of the alternative measures
in anticipation of a potential military strike against the Iraqi
oil refineries. Iraqis received 10 liters of gasoline a day for
each car.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Vice-Premier Tariq Aziz also briefed the Saturday cabinet
on the results of the recent meetings held here by UNSCOM chief
Richard Butler on the removal of the Iraqi mass destruction
weapons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
