<HEADLINE> Philippine Ruling Party Proclaims Presidential Bet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 24 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine ruling Lakas-NUCD
party on Saturday officially proclaimed its presidential and vice
presidential candidates, and the senatorial ticket in the May 11
general elections.
</P>
<P>
At the party's national convention, Philippine President Fidel
Ramos declared his choice Jose de Venecia, speaker of the House of
Representatives, as the Lakas' presidential bet.
</P>
<P>
Senator Gloria Macapagal-Arroyo, formerly a presidential
aspirant, was announced as the governing party's vice presidential
candidate.
</P>
<P>
Ramos, who is chairman of the ruling party, also named the
party's 12 senatorial candidates, most of whom are incumbent
cabinet members including Finance Secretary Robert de Ocampo.
</P>
<P>
Under the country's election law, these incumbent cabinet
members will have to resign soon after filing candidacy with the
Commission on Election (Comelec).
</P>
<P>
Ramos had been given the blanket authority by the ruling party
last November to choose the Lakas presidential and vice
presidential candidates in order to prevent the party from
breaking up.
</P>
<P>
Ramos urged the electorate to choose Lakas bets because of "the
accomplishments of the present administration in terms of
fulfilling its campaign promises and commitments."
</P>
<P>
He assured the people that the administration party's
candidates will carry on the economic reforms and other track
records of the Ramos administration.
</P>
<P>
But according to a recent opinion poll conducted by an
independent pollster, Jose de Venecia's approval ratings still
lagged far behind Vice President Joseph Estrada, the presidential
candidate of the main opposition party -- Struggle of Patriotic
Filipino Masses.
</P>
<P>
Estrada, a formerly popular movie star, has been leading many
surveys due to the support from ordinary masses. His running mate
is Senator Edgardo Angara.
</P>
<P>
Besides Estrada and de Venecia, there are two other proclaimed
presidential contenders -- former defense secretary Renato de
Villa and Manila Mayor Alfredo Lim.
</P>
<P>
In the coming weeks, at least two more presidential hopefuls,
including Senator Miriam Defensor-Santiago, are expected to
declare their candidacy.
</P>
<P>
Under the election law, the country's presidential, vice
presidential, congressional and local elections will be held
simultaneously on May 11.  
</P>
</TEXT>
