<HEADLINE> 4 More Private Banks in Indonesia to Merge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Four more private banks in
Indonesia are merging in a bid to strengthen their operation
capacity, Antara News Agency reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The four banks, namely Bank Umum Nasional, Bank Bukopin, Bank
Tugu and Bank Duta, signed a Memorandum of Understanding on the
merger here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Managing Director of Bank Duta Muchtar Mandala said after the
signing ceremony that the merged bank could become reality in late
June 1998, and will have combined assets of 21.2 trillion rupiah
(one U.S. dollar equals 12,000 rupiah now) and total equity of
1.395 trillion rupiah.
</P>
<P>
He said the merger establishes a strong bank that can serve the
public in the global era.
</P>
<P>
This is the second merger of private banks in the country. On
January 18, five private banks had decided to merge into one in
order to cope with the increasing globalization of financial
services.
</P>
<P>
At the end of October last year, the Indonesian government
closed 16 insolvent private banks aimed at making the banking
sector more healthy.
</P>
<P>
On December 31, the government also announced a plan to merge
four state banks into one and provide foreign banks of
international reputation with the opportunity to become
shareholding partners.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia has about 200 private banks and about 50 percent of
them are regarded as unhealthy banks with various financial
problems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980124.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Government Departments, Factories Move out of Historic City (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SUZHOU, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Twenty-seven Suzhou city
government departments have moved out from downtown buildings to
the suburbs to protect the 2,000-year-old city in east China's
Jiangsu Province, which is famous for its traditional gardens and
beautiful scenery.
</P>
<P>
The move, as well as relocating 160 factories, is aimed at
reviving Suzhou's traditional flavor, according to local officials.
</P>
<P>
"Only by such moves, instead of protecting single relics, can
the whole layout and style of the historic city be preserved,"
said Guo Zhan, director of Cultural Relics Protecting Department
with the State Bureau of Cultural Relics.
</P>
<P>
According to Guo, 99 cities all over the country have been
listed as historic cities under state protection since the 1980s,
including Suzhou.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the Chinese government for the first time applied
for historic cities to be added to UNESCO's World Heritage
List. The candidates included two small cities -- Lijiang in
Yunnan Province and Pingyao in Shanxi Province, and one big city
-- Suzhou.
</P>
<P>
"Actually we chose part of it -- the traditional gardens --
instead of the whole Suzhou city, " Guo said, "That did not mean
that we were reluctant to choose the city as whole. We were afraid
that the condition of the whole city was not good enough."
</P>
<P>
According to Guo, experts from the World Heritage Committee who
unanimously agreed to add the traditional gardens in Suzhou to
the list strongly urged the Chinese government to expand the
area's protection.
</P>
<P>
"Some even proposed to inscribe the whole ancient town of
Suzhou, the so-called 'Oriental Venice,' on the World Heritage
List," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980124.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Government Departments, Factories Move out of Historic City (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"The moving out of government departments and factories is just
part of the local effort to preserve the traditional style of the
city as a whole," Guo said.
</P>
<P>
Founded in the Spring and Autumn Period (770-476 BC), Suzhou
first served as capital of the Wu State. It had been ruined and
rebuilt time and again in the following 2,500 years, never losing
its status as a local economic and political center.
</P>
<P>
Long famous for its beautiful scenery and traditional gardens,
the city's pollution problems began to increase in the 1950s with
a rising population and more factories.
</P>
<P>
To tackle the problem, the city government moved 160 factories
outside the city and closed half of the remaining 60. The only
ones left were those non-polluters with a folk flavor such as
embroidery and traditional music instrument workshops.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the city invested some 30 billion yuan to build 53
residential sections outside the city, each with a floor space of
at least 50,000 square meters.
</P>
<P>
To date, the city has restored 800 ancient lanes and 163 small
bridges, dredged the 35-kilometer ancient waterway, and put up
labels on 200 ancient buildings and 500 old trees.
</P>
<P>
"What Suzhou has done is to set an example for other historic
cities to conserve cultural relics in the light of rapid economic
development," Guo said.
</P>
<P>
He warned that many historic cities are losing their
traditional flavor because of economic changes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980124.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
