<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey: Chinese Citizens Prefer Traditional Festivals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Traditional celebrations,
especially Spring Festival, are more popular among most Chinese
citizens than public holidays, a survey has shown.
</P>
<P>
The survey, carried out by Beijing Horizon Market Survey and
Analysis Company, interviewed 5,000 citizens 18 or older in 10
leading Chinese cities.
</P>
<P>
Following Spring Festival, National Day and Mid-Autumn Festival
are the holidays that Chinese citizens say they like the most.
</P>
<P>
In tandem with the opening up of China, Western festivals such
as Christmas, Valentine's Day and Mother's Day are celebrated by
some Chinese.
</P>
<P>
Public holidays, such as International Labor Day and
International Children's Day, do not rate as highly with Chinese
citizens.
</P>
<P>
The survey also shows that traditional Chinese festivals are
more popular among the elderly, while Western holidays are
comparatively popular with the younger generation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
