<DOCNO> XIE19980124.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Duma Rejects Yeltsin's State Symbols </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 24 (Xinhua) -- The Russian Duma, the lower
house of parliament, rejected a bill Friday for the adoption as
permanent national symbols, the anthem and flag, proposed by
President Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
Itar-Tass news agency reported the presidential measures were,
in the first reading, backed by 107 deputies, while 203 deputies
voted against them, as did seven in abstentia, reports said.
</P>
<P>
The Duma also refused to approve a measure on the anthem
championed by Communist parliament members, which proposed to
re-introduce the post-Soviet anthem written by Alexander
Alexandrov in the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
The white, blue and red tricolor flag, the double-headed eagle
and the melody composed by Mikhail Glinka, known as the Patriotic
Song, have been in use since 1993 when Yeltsin introduced them by
decree.
</P>
<P>
The decree was not legally binding because it lacked a formal
acceptance by the parliament.
</P>
<P>
Communist deputies, who dominate the Duma, opposed the
presidential bill, saying that the tricolor flag had been used by
Russian traitors in World War II, and that the double-headed eagle
was ambiguous in its significance.
</P>
<P>
They proposed in a Duma session last April to re-introduce the
post-Soviet anthem, the hammer and sickle flag and the former
Soviet Russia emblem.
</P>
<P>
In the Friday meeting, the Duma reviewed only the anthem in the
Communists' measure.
</P>
<P>
Under the Russian constitution, a bill must win a two-thirds
majority in the Duma, as well as a three-fourths majority in the
Federation Council (the upper house), to be approved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
