<HEADLINE> U.S. Physicist Establishes Fund for Chinese Students </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 24 (Xinhua) -- A fund, named after
U.S. physicist of Chinese origin Tsung-Dao Lee and his late wife,
has been established in Beijing to help Chinese college students
receive training in scientific institutes.
</P>
<P>
Professor Tsung-Dao Lee has donated a large amount of personal
savings to support visits to and training in scientific institutes
in China for top college students.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Rongji, Vice-premier and a member of the Standing Committee
of the Political Bureau of the Chinese Communist Party Central
Committee, sent a congratulatory letter for the fund's signing
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The fund shows Lee and his family members' concern for China's
scientific education and training and for the cultivation of young
people, said Wen Jiabao, a member of the Political Bureau and a
member of the secretariat of the CPC Central Committee, who
attended the ceremony Friday in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The fund will first be applied to Fudan, Beijing, Lanzhou and
Suzhou universities, and will be spread to other universities and
colleges in the future.
</P>
<P>
Lee was awarded the Nobel Prize in Physics in 1957 jointly with
Chen Ning Yang for their analysis of the law of parity
conservation. He was elected as one of the first group of foreign
academicians to the Chinese Academy of Sciences in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
