<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southwestern China City Holds Lantern Show </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, January 24 (Xinhua) -- The Fifth International
Dinosaur Lantern Show, dubbed the "first lantern in the world," is
on display in Zigong, a city in southwest China's Sichuan Province.
</P>
<P>
More than 60 sets of huge lanterns and nearly 10,000 handicraft
lanterns from China are in the show as well as exotic lanterns
brought by more than 20 countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
Nights in Zigong are ablaze with thousands of colorful lanterns.
</P>
<P>
The history of the show can be traced back to the Tang Dynasty
(618-907). The lantern show is one of the most famous Chinese folk
celebrations along with the Kite Festival in Weifang in east
China's Shandong Province.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1960s, the city has held 11 large-scale lantern
shows, four of which have been international dinosaur lantern
shows. The lantern show has been displayed in 38 cities across
China and in seven countries and regions including Singapore,
Thailand and Japan, with an attendance of more than 40 million
people.
</P>
<P>
The show is scheduled to close March 9. During the 48-day show,
the city has also sponsored a trade fair including exhibitions of
industrial products and automobiles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980124.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Labor Ministry Urges Coal Mines to Improve Safety </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 24 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Labor today
issued an urgent circular to coal mines across the country urging
them to take effective measures to enhance safety in operation
during the Spring Festival.
</P>
<P>
The circular said that, compared with the previous year, the
overall number of accidents in China's coal mines decreased in
1997, but there was a sharp rise in the number of major and
extremely serious accidents.
</P>
<P>
Statistics showed that last year the coal mining sector had 102
major accidents that each claimed more than 10 lives and killed a
total of 2,028 miners. The major accidents were up by 21.42
percent and deaths by 29.83 percent over 1996.
</P>
<P>
"This is the worst record in the coal mining industry since the
founding of New China in 1949," the circular noted, adding that
three major accidents each killing at least 10 people had happened
already this year.
</P>
<P>
The labor ministry demanded that all coal mines and their
competent departments try to remove potential dangers that could
lead to accidents, improve safety regulations, analyze and draw
lesson from various accidents of 1997, and take effective measures
to ensure mining safety throughout 1998.
</P>
<P>
The ministry also urged local governments at all levels to halt
illegal mining operations by unlicensed small coal mines, as well
as the production of licensed mines without basic safety
guarantees.
</P>
<P>
"Labor departments across the country should also intensify
their supervision over safety in operation in coal mines, and
investigate every accident seriously," the circular concluded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980124.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angola, Israel to Launch Anti-Mine Publicity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
Campaign
</P>
<P>
LUANDA, January 24 (Xinhua) -- The Angolan and Israeli
governments and the United Nation Childern's Fund (UNICEF) are to
unfold a joint publicity Campaign to raise Angolans' awareness
about the danger of mines.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Ambassador to Angola Tamara Golan said here today
that three Israeli young volunteers arrived at Luanda on Friday
as the first batch of Israeli volunteers for the tripartite
campaign.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli volunteers who have a good anti-mine knowledge#,
Golan said, are qualified for the job.
</P>
<P>
There are many landmines in Angola and mine clearance is a
long-term work, she said, adding that it is necessary to offer
Angolan people, especially the childern with the information
about landmines.
</P>
<P>
The campaign, which will last for 12 months, is the biggest
anti-mine campaign involving foreigners since the 1994 Lusaka
Peace Protocol, Golan said.
</P>
<P>
Angola claims to have over 10 million mines deployed during
the three decades of anti-colonialism and civil wars throughout
the country and only about 7,500 mines have been cleared in the
past three years.
</P>
<P>
Over 70,000 Angolans have been injured by landmines up to now
and reports of mine injuries are appearing on newspapers almost
everyday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
