<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Beginning For China's Relations With Britain, France (1) by Zhang Rongdian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Beijing has been active
diplomatically with visits by Britain's Foreign Secretary Robin
Cook and France's Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine, giving China
increasing importance in the international arena and making it a
force to be reckoned with.
</P>
<P>
This is Cook's first visit to China since the Chinese
government resumed exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong on
July 1, 1997. China and Britain worked together for a smooth
transfer of power and stable transition, clearing away political
barriers between the two countries and turning a new page in
bilateral cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Britain's Prime Minister Tony Blair, in his meeting with
President Jiang Zemin and Premier Li Peng on June 30, 1997, said
that the two countries could usher in a new chapter of bilateral
relations and a new starting point.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Cook said that Britain hopes for a fresh
beginning in Sino-British relations and wishes to engage in
wind-ranging cooperation with China under new circumstances.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese side welcomed the positive attitude of the British
government toward advancing bilateral relations and its
suggestions and proposals for bilateral cooperation and high-level
exchanges.
</P>
<P>
Friendly and cooperative ties between China and France have
moved ahead thanks to joint efforts since the two countries issued
a joint communique on normalizing relations in January of
1994. During French President Jacques Chirac's visit to China last
May, President Jiang and Chirac signed a joint statement
announcing the establishing of a comprehensive partership geared
to the 21st century, laying a foundation for bilateral ties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980124.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
