<DOCNO> XIE19980124.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Government Providing Drinking Water for Eastern Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 24 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government is
working to ease the drinking water shortage for 400,000 people in
the city of Xuzhou in Jiangsu Province before the Spring Festival
(January 28) by using underground water sources and diverting
water from the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
Local water was seriously affected by pollution of the
Beijing-Hangzhou Grand Canal, which became worse at the beginning
of the month. The provincial government has allocated funds for
new drinking water sources and the city government has ordered
major industrial water consumers to control their intake.
</P>
<P>
The city has also sent fire trucks out twice a day to provide
water for local people who do not have enough water for daily use,
and water companies' wells are being fullly used. Companies that
have their own wells and supplies have agreed to make them
available to city residents.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the canal has been used mainly for navigation
in recent years and its water quality is not very good. Nearby
Jiangsu Province has started diverting water from the Yangtze into
the canal to dilute the pollution.
</P>
<P>
Last September's drought meant the city had to get water from
the canal, intensifying the pollution problem, according to a
study by the State Environmental Protection Agency and the Water
Resources Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Some paper mills along the upper reaches of the canal, in
Shandong Province, discharged waste water into the canal, causing
long-term pollution, the study found.
</P>
<P>
The head of one of the mills and a deputy-director of an
environmental protection agency in the city of Linyin in Shandong
who were responsible for the pollution have already been dealt
with, says Liu Zhihong, a member of the State Environmental
Protection Agency's Water Office.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Shandong and Jiangsu have temporarily closed down
paper mills that are sources of pollution, and water quality in
the canal has improved since these steps were taken, but further
action is needed before it really can be used by locals, a Xuzhou
Environmental Protection Agency official says.
</P>
<P>
The city's waterworks, which used to provide 300,000 tons of
water a day, can now only supply five tons for the city's
residents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
