<HEADLINE> Chinese Foreign Ministry Comments On Meetings between Clinton And Mid-East Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 24 (Xinhua) -- China today expressed its
regret that no substantial progress had come from the recent talks
between US President Bill Clinton and the Israeli and Palestinian
leaders in Washington.
</P>
<P>
China's Foreign Ministry Spokesman Zhu Bangzao made this remark
when asked to comment on Clinton's talks with Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu and Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
He said that China appreciates the efforts in the Middle East
peace process by the international community and that it believes
that the long-standing impasse in the peace process is
unprofitable for both sides and will have a negative effect on
regional peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that the parties concerned will implement the
agreements to achieve practical and concrete results in the peace
process in accordance with the United Nations resolutions
and 'land for peace' principles formulated at the Madrid peace
conference," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
