<DOCNO> XIE19980124.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Chinese Looking To Buy Houses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Most Chinese, even now, are
used to the idea of living in housing provided by their work unit,
but are becoming aware of the fact that their unit may no longer
be offering free housing.
</P>
<P>
This means that they have to get ready to buy and more Chinese
are taking an interest in buying a house of their own, especially
since China's housing reforms are increasing and are expected to
mean greater development of the real estate market.
</P>
<P>
The key point in this is increasing individual demand and
promoting commercial housing, according to the Construction
Ministry. So, the governor of the People's Bank of China, Dai
Xianglong, recently announced that some 100 billion yuan (about
12.5 billion U.S. dollars) will be used for housing loans this
year, in a bid to encourage the purchases.
</P>
<P>
The bank is encouraging all commercial banks to provide loans
for mortgages that are long-term, if necessary.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that housing is an immediate problem for most
ordinary Chinese and the market is one solution and a way to
contribute to rapid and smooth economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The country's housing market has been picking up after being in
a slump for two years, and some municipalities like Shanghai and
Tianjin, and provinces like Shangdong and Jiangsu have been
encouraging people to buy.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics, 58.7 percent of the housing sold from
January to November of 1997 went to individual buyers, a
year-on-year increase of 27.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
China will have more policies to help residents, based on their
income, and will continue the Comfortable Housing Project, whose
purpose is to help low-income people.
</P>
<P>
The total amount of residential housing built in 1996 was 310
million sq.m., or 8.7 sq.m. per person.
</P>
<P>
Some industry insiders predict that private housing will become
part of the mainstream of the real estate sector, as the glut of
hotels, offices, and luxury buildings looms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
