<HEADLINE> Iran Regards US Extraterritorial Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 24 (Xinhua) -- A senior Iranian official said
Saturday that the U.S. extraterritorial sanctions against other
countries violated international norms and laws.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening session of the Asian-African Legal
Consultative Committee (AALCC) Seminar on Extraterritorial
Application of Domestic Jurisdiction, Iranian Deputy Foreign
Minister for international affairs and AALCC President Javad Zarif
said that the economic sanctions imposed on Cuba, Iran and Libya
were examples of a post-cold war trend to use U.S. economic
power to achieve diplomatic ends.
</P>
<P>
He said that the extraterritorial sanctions violated the
principles of sovereignty and territorial integrity of states,
non-intervention, self-determination and the rights to
development.
</P>
<P>
The Helms-Burton and D'Amato Acts, which explicitly seek to
overthrow the Cuban government and change the Iranian domestic
and foreign policy, clearly violate the universally accepted
principle of non-intervention in internal and external affairs of
other states and principle of territorial sovereignty, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Territorial sovereignty is an essential foundation of
contemporary international relations," he said, "without respect
for sovereignty, there will be no internationally accepted norms
and rules of conduct."
</P>
<P>
Zarif said that the imposition of extraterritorial sanctions
against third parties interrupts economic cooperation and trade
relations among sovereign states, and extraterritorial application
of national laws such as Helms-Burton and D'Amato Acts which aim
to restrict the right of the peoples of the target states
violates their right to self-determination.
</P>
<P>
The United States announced the Helms-Burton and D'Amato Acts
in 1996, threatening to impose sanctions against companies of
third countries which have economic cooperation with Cuba and
Iran. The acts were universally condemned, even by the
U.S. western allies.
</P>
<P>
"The imposition of sanctions is permissible only by the United
Nations under Chapter VII of the Charter in order to give effect
to Security Council decisions with respect to maintaining or
restoring international peace and security," Zarif said.
</P>
<P>
Fifteen experts from nine members of the 44-state AALLCC
attended the two-day seminar. The AALCC secretariat will deliver
the result of the seminar to the 37th AALCC Session scheduled to
be held in New Delhi in April. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
