<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ningxia Becomes Northwest China's Fishery Base </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, January 24 (Xinhua) -- The land-locked Ningxia Hui
Autonomous Region in northwest China yielded 22,940 tons of
aquatic products in 1997, a record high.
</P>
<P>
The region has become an important fishery base and aquatic
products distribution center in northwest China, with more than 60
percent of the products sold to its neighboring provinces and
autonomous regions such as Gansu, Qinghai, Shannxi, Xinjiang,
Inner Mongolia and Tibet, said Huang Quanfu, director of the
regional bureau for aquatic products.
</P>
<P>
Situated on the plain at the Great Bend of the Yellow River,
Ningxia has favorable natural conditions for fishery development such
as a large number of lakes and long sunshine time.
</P>
<P>
Over the past few years, the region has made efforts to turn
low-lying saline-alkali land into fishponds. Currently, its
fresh-water breeding area has increased to 10,000 hectares.
</P>
<P>
Beside the traditional Yellow River carp, grass carp and silver
carp, other aquatic products such as soft-shelled turtle, bullfrog
and shrimp have also been bred there.
</P>
<P>
"Farmers are encouraged to get rich by engaging in fresh-water
breeding," Huang said. In Yinchuan along, the regional capital,
there are now more than 3,400 households that are specialized in
this business. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
