<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Seen as "Safe Island" in Asian Financial Crisis  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 24 (Xinhua) -- China is able to maintain
itself a "safe island" in the Asian financial crisis and,
moreover, contribute to eventual financial stabilization in the
region, said a senior government official today.
</P>
<P>
China can not be utterly insulated from the impacts of global
economic turbulences as it has implemented a policy of opening to
the rest of the world, said Bao Kexin, Director-General of the
Department of Foreign Trade and Economic Relations of the State
Planning Commission.
</P>
<P>
"But overall, the prospects are good," Bao told Xinhua in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
The Asian financial crisis, which started in July last year
with the sharp devaluation of the Thai currency, the baht, has
snarled Indonesia, the Philippines, Malaysia, the Republic of
Korea, Hong Kong and Japan, with effects rippling to many parts of
the world.
</P>
<P>
Bao explained that China's persisting favorable balance of
international payments and its rapidly expanding foreign exchange
reserves have combined to greatly increase its power to counter
various risks.
</P>
<P>
Official figures show that China has registered surplus on the
current account for four consecutive years, while its foreign
trade surplus reached a record high of 40.3 billion US dollars in
1997.
</P>
<P>
Also last year China utilized overseas investment in the amount
of 51.9 billion US dollars, resulting in a fairly large net inflow
on the capital account. Its foreign exchange reserves reached
139.9 billion US dollars by the end of 1997, the second largest in
the world.
</P>
<P>
Bao said the countries with the largest level of currency
devaluation in the Asian financial crisis have one thing in
common: sustained current-account deficit in their balance sheets
for international payments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980124.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Seen as "Safe Island" in Asian Financial Crisis  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Once capital inflow slows down or stops, capital flight will
ensue and the double effects of the two, exacerbated by
confidence crisis, will result in payment difficulties and
currency devaluation, Bao said.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that China has largely stood out of the financial
turbulence mainly because its exports have not been affected
significantly, its economy has maintained appropriately rapid
growth, its level of foreign debt is well below the
internationally recognized safety limits, and overseas investment
in China has continued to expand.
</P>
<P>
They note that exports of Southeast Asian nations will enjoy
price competitiveness in a period of time as a result of cheaper
currencies, something that has affected China's exports of some
products.
</P>
<P>
But due to limited overlapping in exports and disparity in
import and labor costs between China and those countries, currency
devaluation in the region will have limited impacts on China's
overall exports, the experts say.
</P>
<P>
The latest statistics show that China's exports in the fourth
quarter of last year grew 32.9 percent on a yearly basis, in a
contrast to a 15.5 percent rise in imports.
</P>
<P>
Qiu Xiaohua, chief economist of the State Statistical Bureau,
said that the Chinese economy has embarked on a healthy track of
"high growth and low inflation" and is expected to grow by 8-10
percent this year.
</P>
<P>
Under the situation of ample supply of both production and
consumer goods, imports will go down if exports drop, and this is
a general rule that has been proved in the recent years, Qiu said.
</P>
<P>
"From the perspective of macro economics, trade deficit is
unlikely at a time when the overall savings rate is much higher
than that of investment," he said.
</P>
<P>
Bao said that encouraged by China's increasingly open policy
and improving infrastructure and investment environment, overseas
investors are keen on the huge China market of 1.2 billion people.
</P>
<P>
Though investment from Southeast Asian countries has slowed
down, overall overseas investment in China will continue to grow
robustly this year, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980124.0129 </DOCNO>
