<HEADLINE> Iran Welcomes Resumption of Tajik Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Iran has expressed welcome to
the resumption of the peace talks between the Tajik government and
opposition after a week-long standoff, Iran's official news
agency IRNA reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Iran welcomes the resumption of the talks and it is encouraging
that neither side of Tajikistan has allowed the process of
national reconciliation to be damaged, said Iranian Foreign
Ministry spokesman Mahmoud Mohammadi Friday.
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi voiced Iran's support for the peace-seeking efforts
of the Tajik government and Islamic movement.
</P>
<P>
He hailed the move as a sign of commitment of either side to
national reconciliation, stability and development and a major
step to promote economic development and reconstruction of the
war-torn Central Asian country.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the Tajik opposition suspended its work in the
National Reconciliation Commission to protest government's failure
to respect a peace agreement signed last year.
</P>
<P>
The commission is working for the implementation of the
agreement, under which the government has promised to offer 30
percent of the government posts to the opposition.
</P>
<P>
Iran, one of the guarantors of the agreement, has shown great
concern about the decision of the Tajik opposition.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi has urged the neighbors
of Tajikistan and concerned world organizations to make efforts to
save the peace process.
</P>
<P>
With the efforts made by U.N. representative Gerd Dietrich
Merrem and some countries, the Tajik opposition has agreed to
resume its work at the National Reconciliation Commission.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
