<HEADLINE> Baltic States to Strengthen Regional Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Leaders from 11 Baltic Sea
countries conducted a summit on Friday in Riga, capital of Latvia,
discussing regional economic cooperation, crime-fighting and the
European Union enlargement.
</P>
<P>
The leaders, present at the second Council of the Baltic Sea
States (CBSS), also discussed energy issue and agreed to create an
integrated gas market and power network in the region.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed to hold an energy ministerial meeting in Oslo,
Norway, soon to further discuss the matter.
</P>
<P>
Further, they called on international financial institutions to
enhance their investment in the Baltic Sea States, and expressed
willingness to improve investment environment in their own
countries.
</P>
<P>
The leaders also discussed issues of EU enlargement, the
strengthening of Russia-EU ties, the promotion of Russia's
accession into the World Trade Organization and closer cooperation
in environmental protection and anti-organized crime fight.
</P>
<P>
In a declaration after the meeting, the leaders noted to work
together to create a "stable, democratic, prosperous and truly
united Europe without divisions."
</P>
<P>
The CBSS was founded in 1992, with member states including
Denmark, Estonia, Lithuania, Russia, Latvia, Norway, Poland,
Finland, Germany, Iceland, Sweden and the European Union
Commission. Its first summit was held in Visby, Sweden in May,
1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
