<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Allows Some Foreign Labors Part-time Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait has decided to
allow some of the foreign laborers in the country to do part-time
jobs to streamline foreign labor, local English daily Arab Times
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The laborers working in Kuwaiti government sector and some
private establishments such as banks and shareholding companies
can take part-time jobs in the private sector, Kuwaiti Minister of
Social Affairs and Labor Ahmad Khaled Al-Kulaib was quoted by the
daily as saying.
</P>
<P>
But foreign employees in other private establishments are
banned from taking part-time jobs, Al-Kulaib added.
</P>
<P>
The measures were taken following a campaign to clear illegal
foreign laborers in Kuwait and tighten the screws on the
recruitment of foreign manpower.
</P>
<P>
The campaign is aimed at streamlining foreign labor in the
Gulf sheikdom which depends mainly on foreign laborers, especially
in its private sector, according to Al-Kulaib.
</P>
<P>
"We want to reform the labor market regarding salary,
profession, age and nationality to create job opportunities for
Kuwaitis in the private sector," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the minister announced that no more work permits
will be issued to unskilled foreign expatriates and only those
trained and with professional expertise will be recruited.
</P>
<P>
There are 585,000 foreign laborers in Kuwait out of a
population of about 1.6 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
