<HEADLINE> Zambian Mine Union Happy With Privatization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Mine Workers Union of Zambia (MWUZ)
has expressed its happiness with the on-going privatization of the
country's mining industry.
</P>
<P>
Zambia Daily Mail today quoted MWUZ President Paul Kafumbe as saying
that the union is happy that the government has put a lot of care and
caution in the privatization of the mines.
</P>
<P>
He told a MWUZ conference in Livingstone in southern Zambia that
adequate consultations and explanations have been done with the
investors over the future cooperation with new managements.
</P>
<P>
He thanked the government for making it a condition the new
investors recognize the MWUZ as the sole representative
and negotiating organ of mine workers.
</P>
<P>
Kafumbe said the privatization of Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines
(ZCCM), the only mining corporation in the country, should not only
increase production but also provide opportunities for more
jobs for workers.
</P>
<P>
He urged the government to consider putting a union representative
on the boards of directors to enable the union to intervene and put in
their decisions at the highest level to protect the interests of
workers.
</P>
<P>
On the political front, he said that MWUZ stressed the importance of
the rule of law, separation of powers and dialog as pillars of
democratic governance.
</P>
<P>
As a union it condemns undemocratic means of wrestling power, he
said. The ballot and meaningful dialogue are the best means of
strengthening Zambia's young and vibrant democracy, the union leader
stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
