<HEADLINE> 40,000 Ugandans Return Home in W. Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Some 40,000 Ugandans who fled
their home have returned to their homes in western Uganda, the
New Vision reported today.
</P>
<P>
Among them, 25,000 have returned from the Democratic Republic
of Congo, and 15,000 are the internally displaced local
residents, said Edward Masiga, the resident Commissioner of
Bundibugyo district.
</P>
<P>
These people are driven from their homes by the rebels of the
Allied Democratic Forces (ADF) who invaded the district a year
ago. Over 60,000 people were displaced during the peak of the
fighting between the rebels and the government troops, the
official added.
</P>
<P>
But there are still some Ugandans remained in the Democratic
Republic of Congo, he said.
</P>
<P>
Francis Katende, the coordinator of the Ugandan army operation
in the region, told the paper that the situation in the region
has returned normal in many places and assured that the rebel
remnants will be wiped out gradually.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that there are still hundreds of ADF remnants
remained in deep mountain areas between the Democratic Republic
of Congo and Uganda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
