<HEADLINE> China's Shanxi Province Gets Record Amount of Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, January 24 (Xinhua) -- The vice-governor of China's
Shanxi Province, Xue Rongzhe, said recently that 1997 had been a
peak year for the northern province's use of overseas investment.
</P>
<P>
Last year, it signed 185 contracts involving 1.013 billion
U.S. dollars of funds from abroad, and the amount of foreign funds
used was 375 million U.S. dollars, a 53 percent rise over 1996.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investment is a very important part of Shanxi's fixed
assets, and 65 percent of it comes from government and
international financial institution loans. There have been
projects each having more than five million U.S. dollars
investment in manufacturing, power supply, service, property, the
building industry, communications, and telecommunications, Xue
said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign-funded enterprises employed 120,000 people and their
combined exports accounted for eight percent of the province's
total.
</P>
<P>
Xue said that his province will encourage overseas investors to
get involved in more coal, power, agriculture, communications, and
raw material projects over the next few years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
