<HEADLINE> Burundi to hold Ministerial Talks With Great </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ARUSHA, TANZANIA, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Burundian Foreign
Minister Luc Rukingana has said that his country would hold the
first ever ministerial talks with the countries of the Great
Lakes Region who had imposed economic sanctions on Burundi early
next month in the Ugandan capital of Kampala.
</P>
<P>
Rukingama, who was attending the workshop on African conflict
resolution here, said Friday that he was waiting for the invitation
from the Ugandan government for the ministerial talks which will be
attended by foreign ministers from Tanzania, Kenya, the special
envoy of Secretary-General of the United Nations and the former
Tanzanian President Julius Nyerere, the major mediator for the
Burundi problem.
</P>
<P>
Participants at the workshop, which closed Friday, called on
the international community to lift the sanctions on Burundi.
</P>
<P>
The over-all economic sanctions imposed on Burundi since July
31, 1996, Rukingama said, has rendered enormous destruction to
Burundian economy, leading a four percent economic growth before
the sanction to a negative growth and the exchange rate between
the Burundian Franc and U.S. Dollar down from 1:240 to 1:400.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Burundian government is determined to hold
talks with all political parties in the country to push ahead the
national reconciliation process.
</P>
<P>
However, Leone Ndarubagiye, a leader representing the
oppossition National Council for Defense of Democracy (CNDD) at
the Arusha workshop, said that his organization would fight to
the end with the government which has been refusing to have talks
attended by all political parties.
</P>
<P>
He said that his organization welcomes the sanctions, which he
said, have put great pressure on the government but hurt very
little to the self-sufficient Burundi people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980124.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Revenue Collection Rise 9.71 percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's revenue collection
in the first half of the current fiscal year rose by 9.71 percent
to 62.65 billion taka (1.39 billion U.S. dollars) as compared with
the previous corresponding period, the National Board of Revenue
(NBR) said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
However, the actual collection from July to December in the
current fiscal year beginning July 1 fell short of the target of
68.03 billion taka (about 1.5 billion dollars), the NBR said.
</P>
<P>
The NBR listed a number of reasons for the shortfall, including
a drastic decline of import duty following the fall in imports,
labor unrest at the Chittagong Port, the slowdown in industrial
production, huge losses in revenues resulting from large-scale
cross-border smuggling.
</P>
<P>
If these problems are not solved, the revenue target of 150
billion taka (about 3.31 billion dollars) for the current fiscal
year could not be met, the NBR warned.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
