<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Starts Construction Work On New Subway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Work on a second subway in
China's leading industrial and commercial center, from Jing'an
Temple in Shanghai's western part and ending at Longdong Road in
the Pudong New Area, has been approved by government departments.
</P>
<P>
The projected 13.6-km subway project will cost 10.5 billion
yuan (1.2 billion U.S. dollars), some of which will be covered by
government loans from Germany, France, and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Work is now being done on tunnels, stations, and parking lots,
with some equipment provided by American, German, and French
manufacturers. The subway is scheduled for completion in the
year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Work began in the mid-1980s. The first part, a 16.1-km line,
was completed on April 10, 1995. By the end of 1997, it had
carried more than 260 million passengers, with a daily volume of
265,000 and a daily peak of 500,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
