<HEADLINE> Shooting Incidents in Zimbabwe to Be Investigated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 24 (Xinhua) -- All shooting incidents, in
which four people died, during the just ended food riots in
Zimbabwe will be investigated regardless of who was behind them,
police spokesman Superintendent Wayne Bvudzijena said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Ten people were shot and injured by the police during this
week's food riots.
</P>
<P>
Four people died of gunshot wounds during the riots
countrywide. Two of them are possibly to have been shot by
police. The other two are believed to have been shot by a
shopowner and security guards.
</P>
<P>
The army has not fired a single shot since its deployment to
beef up security in Harare and Chitungwiza's high-density
suburbs, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
From Monday to Wednesday, thousands of residents in Harare,
Chitungwiza and other small towns staged demonstrations in
protest against recent prices increases.
</P>
<P>
Some of them looted shops, stoned cars and destroyed property,
causing millions of dollars losses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
