<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Former world No.1 Andre Agassi
of the United States stormed into the fourth round of the
Australian Open in Melbourne today after he beat hapless Italian
Andrea Gaudenzi 6-2, 6-2, 6-0.
</P>
<P>
Lighter, faster and fitter than he has been in two years, the
1995 champion Agassi broke Gaudenzi in the first game of the match
and sped to a 4-0 lead, quickly setting the tone.
</P>
<P>
Agassi has worked strenuously in the gym and on the court over
the past six months and has lost about eight kilograms.
</P>
<P>
And now he sees the results his confidence is building daily.
</P>
<P>
"Even today's match was just a reward for a lot of hard work,"
Agassi said.
</P>
<P>
"It all feels good to me. I have been literally looking forward
to playing, competing and trying to win."
</P>
<P>
The news today was not so gratifying for Australian Andrew Ilie
who was shut out by Chile's No.9 seed in their third round
encounter.
</P>
<P>
Ilie, a qualifier ranked 282, had yet to drop a set in the
tournament but today came up against too classy an opponent.
</P>
<P>
Rios, a quarter-finalist at the Australian Open last year,
wrapped up a straight sets victory, winning 6-2, 6-3, 6-2.
