<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Malaysia's CPO, Tin &AMP; Rubber Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's markets of
crude palm oil (CPO) physicals, tin and rubber closed the week all
stronger.
</P>
<P>
CPO physicals started the week on a soft note. However, it
rebounded from Tuesday onward.
</P>
<P>
January South ended the week at 2,500 ringgit (about 555.55
U.S. dollars) per ton, 150 ringgit (about 33.33 U.S. dollars)
higher from last week's closing of 2,350 ringgit (about 522.22
U.S. dollars) per ton.
</P>
<P>
A crop report for January by private forecaster Ivan Wong
released this week sparked some support in the market but the data
only managed to lift the price on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Wong projected palm oil output for January to go down by 18.3
percent to 510,000 tons over December and also forecast palm oil
stock for end-January at 705,000 tons and exports in January at
660,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
This week saw the tin price on the Kuala Lumpur Tin Market
(KLTM) surging following a further weakening of the ringgit which
fell to 4.5100/400 against the U.S. dollar at the close this week.
</P>
<P>
After a downtrend on the first trading day of the week due to
the rebound of the ringgit, the metal went on the uptrend for four
consecutive days following strong buying interest.
</P>
<P>
The tin price this week improved to 23.43 ringgit (about 5.2
U.S. dollars) per kg against last week's 21.52 ringgit (about 4.78
U.S. dollars) per kg.
</P>
<P>
Accumulated turnover registered a decline to 437 tons from 539
tons last week with European, local and Japanese buyers dominating
transactions in the market.
</P>
<P>
This week, on the Malaysian rubber market, technical
adjustments also helped to push up prices.
</P>
<P>
Against last week's close, February RSS One this week rose 26
sen to 326.00 sen (about 72 U.S. cents) per kg while SMR 20 surged
30.5 sen to 328.00 sen (about 72.8 U.S. cents) per kg.
</P>
<P>
The International Natural Rubber Organization (INRO) daily
market indicator price for January 22 was at 226.48
Malaysia/Singapore cents per kg against 201.07 cents on January
15.
</P>
<P>
The five-day moving average stood at 218.06 cents per kg
against 198.84 cents per kg last week.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
