<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam to Take New Austerity Measures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's Ministry of Planning
and Investment (MPI) has announced its intention of cutting
investment projects of provincial and central governments, local
press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The ministry noted that no more money is to be made available
for the purchase of expensive office equipment.
</P>
<P>
It said the cut was part of a determined government effort to
exercise thrift this year.
</P>
<P>
In a circular issued earlier this week, the MPI said individual
ministries of the central government and provinces should
re-consider their own proposed list of projects intended for
government investment and include only those which were considered
essential.
</P>
<P>
Ministries and provinces should submit their proposed
investment plans for this year to the MPI next month for
consideration on a case by case basis because limited investment
could not cover all proposed projects.
</P>
<P>
As part of the government's call for thrift, the MPI said it
would no longer grant finance to administrative government
agencies for the purchase of air conditioning systems, lifts and
other expensive interior equipment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980124.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
