<DOCNO> XIE19980124.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Could Lose 1 Million Jobs From Asian Crisis: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 23 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. trade deficit could
shoot up by over 100 billion U.S. dollars and lose more than 1
million jobs over the next two years as a result of the Asian
currency crisis, a labor-backed think tank said.
</P>
<P>
The Economic Policy Institute said today that California, New
York, Texas and North Carolina would be the hardest hit, but all
50 states would suffer job losses as plunging Asian currencies
make products from those countries cheaper in the United States.
</P>
<P>
"The recent collapse of Asian currencies and financial markets
will have severe economic consequences for the United States," it
noted.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. deficit in merchandise trade, running close to 200
billion dollars in 1997, could increase by 100 billion to 200
billion dollars over the next two years with a resulting loss in
jobs of between 1.1 million and 2.1 million, according to the
study.
</P>
<P>
The institute's report entitled "American Jobs and the Asian
Crisis" pointed out that while the adverse unemployment effects
from a swelling trade deficit could be offset by aggressive
interest rate reductions by the Federal Reserve, but it was not
clear how the Fed would take a fast reaction.
</P>
<P>
The EPI study projected that a 100 billion dollar increase in
the merchandise trade deficit would result in 1.05 million lost
jobs, 726,134 of them coming from manufacturing industries.
</P>
<P>
Among the hardest hit industries would be industrial machinery
and equipment, including computers, with a loss of 168,734 jobs;
electronic equipment, including telephones and other
telecommunications products, 122,026 lost jobs; apparel and
textiles, 64,694 lost jobs; and transportation, covering autos and
aircraft, 47,787 lost jobs.
</P>
<P>
The states with the biggest job losses would be California,
126,681; Texas, 65,024; New York, 63,555; and North Carolina,
50,063, the institute said.
</P>
<P>
Many economists have cut down their growth forecasts for 1998
to around 2.5 percent, down from the 3.7 percent in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
