<HEADLINE> U.S. Doubles Deportation of Mexican Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, January 23 (Xinhua) -- United States immigration
authorities deported 2,000 undocumented Mexican children and
adolescents last year, a 100 percent increase over the 1996 figure.
</P>
<P>
This was reported Friday by the director of the Center for the
Attention to Border Minors of Mexico, Jose Ibarra, who said that
655 of the 2,000 undocumented minors reported were assisted by
his institution located on the border city of Ciudad Juarez of the
northern Mexican state of Chihuahua.
</P>
<P>
The director said that most of the deported who resided in the
interior of the country received lodging from the Mexican
authorities.
</P>
<P>
Patricia Cabrera, spokeswoman for the System for the Integral
Development of the Family, said some of the minors who have been
returned to Mexico and remained in Ciudad Juarez tried again to
enter the neighboring country by being engaged in illegal
activities including theft.
</P>
<P>
She explained that on the basis of studies on the deported
minors, the major causes that make those minors leave their homes
are vagrancy, curiosity, disintegration of the family, and the
desire to earn money to help their families.
</P>
<P>
Cabrera said that through its programs, the institute is trying
to taking the minors out of the streets and convince them to
return to their homes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
