<HEADLINE> Argentina Floats First Bond in Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Argentina issued its first
bonds in euro at a five-year term on Friday, the Foreign Ministry
said.
</P>
<P>
The 400 million euro of bonds, equivalent to 439.2 million
U.S. dollars, were issued by the SBC Wasrburg Dillon Read Swiss
bank.
</P>
<P>
The annual bond yield (on semiannual basis) in dollars is 8.586
percent, 420 basic points above the U.S. Treasury Bond, the
ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The Economy Ministry's Financing Undersecretary Miguel Kiguel
stressed that the euro will replace the market of lire, marks, and
French francs, and might become the second source of financing for
Argentina.
</P>
<P>
Argentina floated five bonds with a total amount of 2 billion
dollars in different European currencies in 1997, with the
condition of the convertibility to the euro. 
</P>
</TEXT>
