<HEADLINE> Veteran Deputy to People's Congress in Tibet (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Tibet, as well as the rest of the
country, suffered from enormous setbacks during turmoil of the
Cultural Revolution (1966-1976).
</P>
<P>
"People are free to do anything they want, and the deputies to
the People's Congresses could not play their roles well," Gyain
said, "it seemed very democratic then, however, it is destructive."
</P>
<P>
Since the third plenum of the 11th Central Committee of the
Communist Party of China held in late 1978, Tibet has witnessed
unpresidented progress in all aspects of life.
</P>
<P>
"Nowadays, people have a better understanding of their power,
and know how to express their views through legal means," added
Gyain, "as a result, they are stricter in choosing their deputies
to the people's congress."
</P>
<P>
Gyain attaches great importance to the opinions of the voters,
and habitually seeks advices from them.
</P>
<P>
"Most deputies to the First People's Congress of the Nedong
County could not write and read," said Gyain, "however, lots of
deputies to the Ninth People's Congress have graduated from
universities or professional schools."
</P>
<P>
"Though 66 already, I am attending the night school," she said,
"as I hate to be lagged behind the time."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
