<HEADLINE> Talks on South Korean Debt to Continue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Talks between a South Korean
delegation and international bankers will continue next Monday, as
both sides are still seeking ways to settle terms on resolving
South Korea's debt issue, sources said Friday.
</P>
<P>
South Korea was reported to have asked international bankers to
extend its 25 billion U.S. dollars of short-term debt to one to
five years, sources said at the end of Friday's talks at
Citibank's New York headquarters.
</P>
<P>
The bankers, including those from the United States, Germany
and France, discussed the matter, but have not reached any
agreement on the terms at which the funds will be restructured.
</P>
<P>
The French bank Societe Generale was said to have proposed a
price of 4 percentage points over the London Interbank Offered
Rate, or LIBOR.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean delegation arrived here last Sunday. Reports
had predicted that some results might come out from the talks on
Friday, but so far no official announcement has been made. 
</P>
