<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Thai-Malaysia Cooperation in Dealing Separatists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Thai army commander-in-chief
Gen. Chettha Thanajaro said there would be more cooperation
between Thailand and Malaysia in a crackdown on separatists active
in southernmost Thai provinces.
</P>
<P>
Chettha said on Friday that in the future Thai security forces
would be able to make "hot pursuits" of separatists into
Malaysia's border areas, the Bangkok Post reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
He was commenting on terrorism conducted by separatists who
want to set up an independent Muslim state in Southern Thailand.
</P>
<P>
During the last two months, over a dozen bomb attacks were made
at schools, bridges, police posts and other public places.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, three separatist suspects were arrested.
They reportedly belong to the New Pattani United Liberation
Organization.
</P>
<P>
Thai authorities will make continued efforts to arrest the
remaining members of the separatist movements to restore lasting
peace to the south, Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
He said the problem was not over with the arrest of the three,
because the bomb attacks were not the work of a single person.
</P>
<P>
"It's an organized movement and we cannot solve the problem by
just arresting a few people," Chuan said.
</P>
<P>
The separatists, who make Malaysia their sanctuary, often cross
the border into Malaysia after carrying out a terrorist act in
Southern Thailand, the newspaper quoted a Thai intelligence
official as saying.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
