<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brief Latin American Cultural News </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, January 23 (Xinhua) -- The following are news
about culture, arts, entertainment and related events which
occurred in the last few days:
</P>
<P>
National Cinema Festival Starts in Nicaragua
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- A festival of Nicaraguan cinema was inaugurated in
the touristic city of Granada in which the work realized by
national cinemakers will be presented during three days.
</P>
<P>
In the inauguration of the festival, organized by the Casa de
los Tres Mundis of Granada, and the Nicaraguan Cinematography
Association, the documental films "Lady Marshall," of Maria Jose
Alvarez, and "Not All the Dreams Have Been Dreamed," of Martha
Clarisa Hernandez were screened.
</P>
<P>
The show will continue with the short features "The Man of One
Single Note," and "Bitumen and Blood, both made by Frank Pineda,
and "Dead of Fright," jointly made by Pineda and Florence Jaugey.
</P>
<P>
Brazil To Build The Biggest Clock of the World
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brasilia, the Brazilian capital, will have the
biggest clock of the world. The idea was started by local TV
channel "Globo" within the "Brazil 500 Years" project, the press
reported.
</P>
<P>
The clock will be 133 feet high, 100 feet wide, and will have a
73 feet diameter face, equivalent to a 10-story building.
</P>
<P>
5th Festival of New Theater Trends Held in Chile
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- The Fifth Festival of New Theater Trends is being
held in this city from the 6th to the 24th of this month, with the
presentation of national and international works.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-one works were considered for the event, organized by
the Theater Department of the University of Chile, of which 17
were sent from this capital, four from regions, and 10 by
international guests.
</P>
<P>
Works from the United States, Italy, Brazil, Argentina, and a
pair of productions from Belgium and Colombia are among the
international guests invited to the festival.
</P>
<P>
Brazilian Presidency To Have Television Channel
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- The Planalto Palace, the Brazilian presidential
residence, will have next month its own television channel, as the
ones the Chamber of Deputies and the Senate have.
</P>
<P>
Social Communication Secretary Sergio Amaral, also presidential
spokesman, said that this channel will broadcast live to the
country the official activities of President Fernando Henrique
Cardoso.
</P>
<P>
Diego Rivera, Frida Kahlo Exhibit Opens in Switzerland
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- The exhibition of Diego Rivera and Frida Kalho
in Switzerland opened Jan. 23 during the celebration of the 20th
anniversary of the Pierre Gianadda Foundation in Martigny.
</P>
<P>
The National Council for Culture and the Arts of Mexico
informed that the exhibit, that will conclude June 1, shows the
work of the two Mexican artists, loaned by important public and
private collections of Mexico, as well as from international
museums, such as the New York Modern Art Museum, and the Phoenix
Museum of Art. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
