<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lewinsky Standing by Affidavit, Lawyer Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 23 (Xinhua) -- A lawyer representing Monica
Lewinsky said on Friday the former White House intern is "at this
time" standing by a sworn affidavit that she did not have a sexual
relationship with President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Sworn and signed on January 7, and submitted to lawyers
handling Paula Corbin Jones's sexual harassment suit against
Clinton, the affidavit contradicts secretly-recorded tapes in
which Lewinsky claimed to have had sexual relations with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Clinton has repeatedly denied the allegation.
</P>
<P>
In the affidavit, Lewinsky stated, "I have the utmost respect
for the president, who always behaved appropriately in my
presence. I have never had a sexual relationship with the
president."
</P>
<P>
She said in the affidavit, "He did not propose that we have a
sexual relationship. He did not offer me employment or other
benefits in exchange for a sexual relationship. He did not deny me
employment or other benefits for rejecting a sexual relationship."
</P>
<P>
Lewinsky's longtime family attorney, William Ginsburg, when
answering reporters' questions, said, "She will stand on the sworn
affidavit at this time."
</P>
<P>
Many people in Washington were waiting to hear what Lewinsky
would say in her deposition, which had been scheduled for Friday,
but was indefinitely delayed by U.S. District Judge Susan Webber
Wright.
</P>
<P>
Lewinsky was reportedly considering invoking her Fifth
Amendment right to decline to answer questions from Jones's
attorneys at the deposition.
</P>
<P>
The tapes in which Lewinsky claimed to have had an affair with
Clinton were recorded with a hidden device by Lewinsky's alleged
friend, Linda Tripp, who has tried previously to serve as a
whistle-blower in the Clinton White House. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
