<DOCNO> XIE19980124.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Exports 27 Million Tons of Coal Last Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 24 (Xinhua) -- China Coal Import and Export
Group (CCIEG) exported 27.48 million tons of coal in 1997, 1.54
million tons more than that of 1996, China Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted Wang Changchun, chairman and president of
the CCIEG, as saying that the company exported 280,000 tons of coke,
an increase of 60.9 percent over 1996.
</P>
<P>
It also exported machinery, electronic equipment and other
commodities valued at 12.2 million U.S. dollars, up 19.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The company's total foreign trade volume was 1.19 billion
U.S. dollars last year, of which the exports made up 1.03 billion
U.S. dollars. It made 400 million yuan of profits in the past
year, according to Wang.
</P>
<P>
The company made great efforts to overcome difficulties brought
along by a stagnant international coal market and decreased coal
import by overseas customers in the wake of the Southeast
Asia's financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
Wang said the company would export more coal by taking more
effective measures in the next three years. The company will tap
new markets in South America and South Asia while cementing its
traditional market shares in Japan, the Republic of Korea and
Europe.
</P>
<P>
It will also start its own fleets to ship coal for export and
will rely on the newly-built Nanning-Kunming Railway to export
more coal to South Asia and Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
By the year of 2000, the CCIEG is expected to export 40 million
tons of coal, representing 80 percent of the country's total
planned coal export.
</P>
<P>
With China National Coal Industry Import and Export Co as its
core, the CCIEG was officially established by merging four other coal
companies in August 1997 and is responsible for doing most of the
country's coal export and import business.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
