<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Transportation in China Surge for Spring Festival </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 24 (Xinhua) -- China's homebound passenger
volume is approaching its peak as the Year of Tiger is just four
days away, Niu Mi, director of Beijing Spring Travel Office was
quoted as saying by today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
"The number of people leaving Beijing by air and train or buses
for the Spring Festival increased from 297,000 on January 8, when
the year's spring travel period stated, to 417,000 on Tuesday,"
Niu said.
</P>
<P>
The figure is expected to surge today and tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 100 pairs of outbound and return trains had been added
to alleviate the spring travel congestion in Beijing, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Between January 8 and 22, a total of 5,265 flights flew to or
left Beijing Capital International Airport, transporting more than
602,900 passengers, Wang Hongbo, an official with Air China,
China's flagship carrier, said.
</P>
<P>
He confirmed: "Tickets for most airlines have sold out." And the
airport terminal building was crowded with anxious passengers.
</P>
<P>
A total of 7.6 million passengers was expected to travel by air
during the 50-day spring travel period, sources from the Civil
Aviation Administration of China (CAAC) said.
</P>
<P>
Based on meticulous market research, the administration has
added 4,256 extra flights or charters to help resolve any
bottleneck in the air.
</P>
<P>
"Air China will dispatch more flights to cover destinations in
the country's southern coastal areas and the Southeast Asia
region," Wang said.
</P>
<P>
He added that as more passengers chose to spend the festival
abroad, his company had planned more flights heading for Bangkok
and Singapore from tomorrow to February 2.
</P>
<P>
Since last November, price cuts in China's air companies have
ranged from five percent to 40 percent, sources from the CAAC
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
