<DOCNO> XIE19980124.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PGR on Probe of Chiapas Massacre </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, January 23 (Xinhua) -- The Attorney General of the
Republic Office (PGR) of Mexico published Friday a report on the
progress made in the investigation of the massacre of 45
indigenous persons in Acteal, Chiapas, which occurred last
December 22.
</P>
<P>
A communique from the PGR says that the investigation of the
killings in the village of Acteal, in the Chenalho municipality,
continues its course, and reiterates that the PGR will apply the
law to all the persons who have some responsibility in the case.
</P>
<P>
The document says that at least 60 persons from several
communities of the Chenalho municipality attacked with firearms a
group of persons, members of the "Las Abejas" (the Bees) group,
who had settled in a camp in the Acteal village.
</P>
<P>
It adds that 20 of the dead persons were women, four of them
pregnant, 18 minors, and seven adult men. 43 of the corpses had
injuries caused by firearms, and two died of skull fractures.
</P>
<P>
The PGR said that at least 15 firearms of several calibers were
used in the massacre, among them five rifles of 7.62 milimeter
bore, better known as "goat's horn."
</P>
<P>
The PGR has detained so far 60 persons, of which 50 were sent
to the disposition of district judges in the state of Chiapas,
where they heard a notification of formal prison. Those persons
remain at the "Cerro Hueco" penitentiary in Tuxtla Gutierrez.
</P>
<P>
Three other detained persons, who are minors, are in the Center
of Diagnosis and Treatment of Minors.
</P>
<P>
The local Public Attorney General Office did not find enough
reasons to incarcerate the remaining seven persons, so they were
released under the reservations of the law.
</P>
<P>
Of those processed, 48 are private citizens and two are former
public officials (Jacinto Arias, Chenalho acting mayor, and Felipe
Vazquez, public security commander).
</P>
<P>
The PGR press communique says that all the cases in which
participated witnesses or alleged responsible, were made following
the law and human rights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
