<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, January 24 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- There had been some movement forward on
certain issues between Iraq and the United Nations Special
Commission (UNSCOM), Russian Ambassador to the United Nations
Sergei Lavrov stressed here Friday.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks after Richard Butler, executive chairman of
the UNSCOM in charge of dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass
destruction, briefed the Security Council on his latest visit to
Iraq. (UN-Russia-Iraq)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BONN -- German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel Friday said that
he has proposed an international action program to help the
Bosnian Serb Republic after the election of a moderate government
there last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued Friday, Kinkel said that the election of
the new Serb government had offered "a great chance to make 1998 a
year of reconstruction, return of refugees and self-sustained
stability in Bosnia." (Germany-Serb Republic)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said Friday
the face-off with Iraq over weapons inspections was "unacceptable"
and should not be allowed to continue.
</P>
<P>
"The situation as Chairman (Richard) Butler (chief U.N. weapons
inspector) described it is unacceptable.... This is not going to
be something that can last much longer," she told a news
conference.
</P>
<P>
Albright said the United States was waiting for Butler's report
to the U.N. Security Council today on his latest trip to Baghdad
seeking to resolve the standoff. (US-Iraq-Arms Inspections)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ARUSHA, Tanzania -- Tanzanian Prime Minister Fredrich Sumaye
Friday urged African countries to enhance their capability to
prevent and resolve conflicts instead of waiting for outside
interference.
</P>
<P>
Sumaye was speaking on behalf of President Benjamin Mkapa at
the closing here of an international workshop on African Conflict
resolution.
</P>
<P>
"The majority of present conflicts on our continent are
essentially of our own making -- whether internally within one
country, or across African borders. Hence their solution will be
realized to a large extent by focusing on the domestic or regional
scene," said Sumaye. (Tanzania-Conflict)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIJING -- China could face a talent deficiency due to its
aging population and rapid economic growth, according to a survey
conducted by China's Association of Senior Citizens.
</P>
<P>
Among more than one million people who have acquired senior
professional titles, the ones below 45 years old account for only
6.3 percent; and those younger than 35, 1.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2000, more than half of China's senior engineers,
researchers and agricultural technicians will go into retirement,
which could result in a talent scarcity for a long period of time,
the survey said. (China-Statistics-Talents)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- As a sovereign state, Iraq's dignity and
legitimate security concerns should be taken into due
consideration, Chinese Permanent Representative to the United
Nations Qin Huasun stressed Friday.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador Qin made the remarks after Richard Butler, the
Executive Chairman of the United Nations Special Commission
(UNSCOM) in charge of dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass
destruction, briefed the Security Council on his latest visit to
Iraq. (China-Iraq) 
</P>
