<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Prime Minister Ends Visit to Chile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Prime Minister Jean
Chretien ended his four-day visit to Chile Friday.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Chretien met with Chilean President Eduardo
Frei and signed an agreement to prevent double taxation on income
and property and tax evasion.
</P>
<P>
The two governments also signed a memorandum of understanding
on educational cooperation and a statement of intentions in the
area of scientific and technological research.
</P>
<P>
Chretien, who was heading a delegation consisting of provincial
prime ministers, federal ministers and 400 businessmen, also
visited Mexico, Brazil and Argentina.
</P>
<P>
In the four days, the two sides signed 66 agreements on
technological, educational, economic, energy and mining
cooperation worth 550 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian prime minister also inaugurated the Gasoducto del
Pacifico pipeline project that will transport natural gas from
Argentina's Neuquen province to Chile, in which Canada's Nova Gas
company held 30 percent of the 400-million-dollar total investment.
</P>
<P>
Chretien said the agreements will strengthen Canadian ties with
Chile.
</P>
<P>
Chile's exports to Canada amounted to 73.5 million dollars in
July-November 1997 after a free trade agreement between the two
countries took effect last July, a 60 percent increase over the
same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
In the same period, the Chile's imports were up 29 percent to
253 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Canada is the second largest investor in Chile with 6 billion
dollars of investments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
