<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Not to Issue Horse Race Lottery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Beijing has no plan of building
a horse race course, said an official with the Beijing Welfare
Lottery Issuing Center.
</P>
<P>
Yan Feng, director of the center, rebutted reports that the
center will support issuance of a horse racing lottery, according
to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Horse racing for betting purposes is not allowed on the Chinese
mainland.
</P>
<P>
Yan made the remarks in response to some rumor reports that a
subsidiary of US-based company, Chancellor, will partner Beijing Dadu
International Jockey Club Co. to open a horse race course and to
issue a lottery in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The reports, released through the Internet since last May, were
accompanied by photocopy of a letter of intent signed by Yan's
center in 1993 and the Beijing Zhida Development Co., a major
shareholder of Dadu. The letter was about the two sides'
cooperation on lottery issuing.
</P>
<P>
"The letter was invalid because it did not get approval from
the Issuing Center of China Social Welfare Lottery," Yan was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Yan's center has informed Zhida last September that the letter
of intent has been officially canceled.
</P>
<P>
Besides, Dadu said it does not have any connections with
Chancellor and its subsidiaries, according to Yan.
</P>
<P>
As a matter of fact, Dadu has not opened for business yet. With
the ban on horse race gambling, the company, although holding the
name "jockey club", cannot hold horse race even if it does open,
Yan was quoted as saying.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
