<HEADLINE> Costa Rican Vice President Denounces U.S. Warning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, January 24 (Xinhua) -- Costa Rican Vice President
Rodrigo Oreamuno denounced Friday the warning made by the U.S.
State Department about the dangers of traveling in Pavones area of
Costa Rica.
</P>
<P>
Oreamuno said some national and foreign media have interviewed
citizens residing in Pavones, as well as foreign tourists, and
they have testified that everything is normal in Pavones of Costa
Rica.
</P>
<P>
"All of them say they feel secure and tranquil, and friendship
is in the air," underscored the Costa Rican Vice President.
</P>
<P>
"We consider it unfair and biased for the Department of State
to warn its citizens against visiting the area."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. warning was made after a U.S. national was killed in
Pavones, next to the Panamanian border last year.
</P>
<P>
"We are trying to make the U.S. government change that
attitude," said Oreamuno.
</P>
<P>
The Costa Rican government has repeatedly denounced the
position of the U.S. government. 
</P>
