<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Talent Shortage Could Pose Development Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 24 (Xinhua) -- China could face a talent
deficiency due to its aging population and rapid economic growth,
according to a survey conducted by China's Association of Senior
Citizens.
</P>
<P>
Among more than one million people who have acquired senior
professional titles, the ones below 45 years old account for only
6.3 percent; and those younger than 35, 1.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2000, more than half of China's senior engineers,
researchers and agricultural technicians will go into retirement,
which could result in a talent scarcity for a long period of time,
the survey said.
</P>
<P>
"The insufficiency of human resources is partly caused by the
Cultural Revolution (1966-1976), which inflicted an interruption
upon the training of a generation of intellectuals," one expert
said.
</P>
<P>
Many intellectuals have gone abroad and stayed in foreign
countries, which also exacerbated the problem. The number of
Chinese students who studied abroad from 1978 to 1996 was 270,000,
and fewer than one-third returned to China, the survey said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
