<HEADLINE> Aquatic Products Industry in Guangxi of China Growing Rapidly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, January 24 (Xinhua) -- The aquatic products industry in
southwest China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region has undergone
rapid expansion because of controlled exploitation and protection
of fishery resources, officials say.
</P>
<P>
Local statistics show that production of the region's aquatic
products in 1997 reached 1.9 million tons, a 7.3 percent
increase over 1996, ranking ninth in the country. Its aquatic
products last year was valued at 10 billion yuan (1.25 billion
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
And the per-capita consumption of aquatic products in the
region rose from 7.7 kilograms in 1990 to the present 23
kilograms.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the region exported more than 20,000 tons of aquatic
products, earning 50 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
So far, the region has 20,000 fishing boats with 600,000
employees and a fish-breeding area of about 200,000 hectares. And
more than 35 aquatic products processing factories have been
built, with an annual processing capacity of 100,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
The coastal cities of Beihai, Qinzhou and Fangchenggang
produce 1.3 million tons of aquatic products every year, worth six
billion yuan (770 million U.S. dollars). The output of sea fishing
accounts for 70 percent of the region's total aquatic products.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the fishing industry will become a driving
force for the local economy.
</P>
<P>
The region is projected to increase its aquatic products by
250,000 tons a year during the Ninth Five-Year Plan
(1996-2000) period, according to the officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
