<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 23 (Xinhua) -- Lower crude-oil prices
weighed down the fourth-quarter earnings of some of the major oil
companies in the United States and the impact may extend to 1998,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Companies such as Chevron and Texaco showed good performances in
the fourth quarter of 1997 but others faired not so well, according
to their latest quarterly reports.
</P>
<P>
Amoco, for example, reported lower earnings, hurt by lower
margins in its petroleum products unit and a drop of 33 percent in
its chemicals unit income.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the continuing sharp decline in oil and natural
gas prices may apply downward pressure on oil companies in their
first quarter earnings and may imply difficulties in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Despite the fact that some firms are performing well now in
their refining and marketing units, this is not going to be enough
to make up for their weaker exploration, production and chemicals
earnings, they said.
</P>
<P>
Oil prices have dropped some five dollars a barrel to the
current levels approaching 15 dollars a barrel since last November
as there have been growing concerns about shrinking demand from
Asia and rising output from the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries.
</P>
<P>
On the New York Mercantile Exchange, crude oil futures plunged
Thursday to the 45-month low.
</P>
<P>
The nearby March crude-oil contract, the futures contract
nearest to physical delivery fell 32 32 cents to 16.04 dollars a
barrel.
</P>
<P>
In overnight trading the contract dropped 45 cents to 15.91
dollars a barrel, the lowest level since April 1994. 
</P>
