<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mix of Cheap Drugs Could Cut Heart Attacks: Researchers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 23 (Xinhua) -- A combination of aspirin and
warfarin is at least 60 percent more effective at preventing heart
attacks than either drug taken alone, British researchers said
today.
</P>
<P>
A study of 5,500 men aged between 45 and 69 at high risk of
disease found that the two drugs taken together reduced the
occurrence of a first heart attack by a third.
</P>
<P>
The result of the seven-year trial, supported by the UK Medical
Research Council, was published in the medical journal The Lancet.
</P>
<P>
It found that over a year, if 1,000 high-risk men were given
the combined treatment, then five heart attacks would be avoided.
</P>
<P>
If the same number were given aspirin or warfarin alone, then
three heart attacks would be avoided. If no treatment was given,
there would be 13 heart attacks.
</P>
<P>
In a commentary in The Lancet, Professor Freek Verheugt,
cardiologist at the University Hospital of Nijmegen, the
Netherlands, said that the trial "clearly indicates that there are
other and less expensive drugs for reducing the incidence of heart
attacks."
</P>
<P>
However, he added that a recommendation that everyone should
take aspirin is not advisable because the incidence of heart
attacks in the general population is so low and the drug does
carry some risk of stomach irritation and bleeding. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980124.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Gov't Records 13.6 Bln Dlr Budget Surplus in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 23 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. federal government
recorded a 13.6 billion U.S. dollar budget surplus in December,
the Treasury Department reported here today.
</P>
<P>
The big surplus helped slim the deficit for the first three
months of fiscal 1998, which started in October to just two-thirds
of the deficit accumulated during the same period of the previous
budget year.
</P>
<P>
December's surplus compares with an 18.5 billion dollar deficit
in the previous December. The budget shortfall for the first
quarter of the fiscal year, was 39.7 billion dollars, down 33
percent from the corresponding period of 1997.
</P>
<P>
That puts the 1998 deficit on track to come in under last
year's 23-year low of 22 billion dollars. President Bill Clinton
is scheduled to submit his 1999 budget to Congress on February 3.
Government officials believe it will mark the first balanced
budget in 30 years.
</P>
<P>
In December, receipts totaled 168 billion dollars, compared
with spending of 154.4 billion dollars. The biggest spending
categories were interest on the public debt, 67.7 billion dollars;
Social Security, 35.6 billion dollars; the Department of Health
and Human Services, including Medicare and Medicaid, 33 billion
dollars; and the military, 25.8 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
For the first quarter of the fiscal year, receipts totaled
386.4 billion dollars, up 11.7 percent from a year ago. Spending
totaled 426.1 billion dollars, up 5.1 percent. Corporate tax
receipts were up 21.5 percent to 51.2 billion dollars and
individual income tax payments 10.7 percent to 176.3 billion
dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
